doctor_vignette: A 129-year-old male presents with severe abdominal pain localized to the right lower quadrant, accompanied by nausea and a low-grade fever. On physical examination, he exhibits tenderness and rebound tenderness in the right lower abdomen with guarding. Laboratory tests reveal an elevated white blood cell count of 14,000/mm³, and an abdominal ultrasound shows a thickened appendix with surrounding fluid, suggestive of acute appendicitis.

A 128-year-old male presents with worsening fatigue and intermittent difficulty in speaking over the past month. Neurological examination reveals decreased strength in the right upper extremity and a positive Babinski sign on the right. MRI of the brain shows multiple hyperintense lesions in the periventricular white matter consistent with demyelination. Cerebrospinal fluid analysis reveals elevated oligoclonal bands.

A 100-year-old female presents to the emergency department with sudden onset shortness of breath and chest pain. On physical examination, she is tachypneic with a heart rate of 110 bpm and has decreased oxygen saturation at 85% on room air. A chest CT angiogram reveals a large pulmonary embolism in the right main pulmonary artery. Her D-dimer level is significantly elevated, supporting the diagnosis.

A 71-year-old female presents with fatigue and decreased appetite for the past several months. On physical examination, she has bilateral lower extremity edema and pale conjunctiva. Laboratory results reveal an elevated serum creatinine level of 2.5 mg/dL and a glomerular filtration rate (GFR) of 30 mL/min. Urinalysis shows proteinuria and hematuria, indicating underlying kidney dysfunction.
actual_diagnosis: Chronic kidney disease, ICD-10 code N18.9

doctor_vignette: A 63-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of bilateral joint pain and stiffness lasting more than six weeks, particularly in her hands and knees. Physical examination reveals swelling, tenderness, and decreased range of motion in the affected joints, along with subcutaneous nodules. Laboratory tests show positive rheumatoid factor and elevated anti-CCP antibodies, alongside a high sedimentation rate indicating inflammation.

A 48-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of persistent cough and increasing shortness of breath over the past few months. Physical examination reveals digital clubbing, wheezing, and decreased breath sounds bilaterally. A chest X-ray shows bronchiectasis, and sputum analysis reveals a high concentration of salt and the presence of Pseudomonas aeruginosa.

A 5-year-old female presents with complaints of fatigue and difficulty concentrating at school. On physical examination, she is noted to have dry skin, thinning hair, and a bradycardic heart rate of 60 beats per minute. Laboratory tests reveal elevated TSH levels of 12 mU/L and low free T4 levels of 0.5 ng/dL, indicating thyroid dysfunction.

A 12-year-old female presents with complaints of increasing muscle weakness, particularly in her arms and eyelids, which worsens with activity and improves with rest. Physical examination reveals ptosis of the left eyelid and generalized weakness in the proximal muscle groups. A serological test shows positive anti-acetylcholine receptor antibodies, supporting the diagnosis.

A 62-year-old female presents with joint swelling and pain in her right knee following a minor fall. Upon examination, there is notable effusion and tenderness in the joint, along with easy bruising on her forearms. Lab results reveal a prolonged activated partial thromboplastin time (aPTT) with normal prothrombin time (PT) and low factor VIII levels, confirming a bleeding disorder.

A 114-year-old female presents with sudden onset of severe chest pain radiating to the back. Physical examination reveals a diastolic murmur and a BP differential of 20 mmHg between the arms. A chest X-ray shows a widened mediastinum, and a CT scan confirms an aortic dissection extending from the ascending aorta to the descending aorta.

A 65-year-old female presents with fatigue, joint pain, and a butterfly-shaped rash on her face. Physical examination reveals swelling in her hands and wrists, along with oral ulcers. Laboratory tests show positive antinuclear antibodies (ANA) and elevated anti-double-stranded DNA antibodies.
actual_diagnosis: Systemic lupus erythematosus, ICD-10 code M32.9

doctor_vignette: A 117-year-old female presents with weight fluctuations and reports binge eating followed by self-induced vomiting. Physical examination reveals dental erosion and electrolyte imbalances, with a potassium level of 2.8 mEq/L. She expresses significant distress regarding her body image and dietary habits, and has a history of anxiety and depression.

An 81-year-old male presents with severe pain in the lower left jaw, exacerbated by chewing. On examination, there is swelling and tenderness over the left mandible, with a noticeable fluctuant mass. Radiographic imaging reveals a periapical radiolucency associated with the affected tooth, indicating an abscess. Vital signs are stable, but the patient shows signs of distress due to pain.

A 79-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of a persistent cough for the past two weeks, associated with mild wheezing and a low-grade fever. On physical examination, there are crackles heard in the lungs and a heart rate of 98 beats per minute. A chest X-ray shows no evidence of pneumonia, and a sputum sample reveals mild bronchial inflammation with no bacterial growth.

An 88-year-old male presents to the emergency department with sudden onset of sharp right-sided chest pain and shortness of breath. On physical examination, he exhibits decreased breath sounds on the right side and tachycardia. A chest X-ray reveals a large right-sided pneumothorax with mediastinal shift. His vital signs show mild hypotension and increased respiratory rate.

A 57-year-old male presents with fatigue and pallor. On examination, he has a smooth, beefy red tongue and mild jaundice. Laboratory tests reveal a low hemoglobin level of 8.5 g/dL, elevated mean corpuscular volume (MCV) of 110 fL, and a positive intrinsic factor antibody test.

A 91-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of severe burning pain and redness in her feet, which worsens with warmth and improves with cooling. On physical examination, her feet are warm, red, and swollen, with a notable increase in temperature compared to her legs. Laboratory tests reveal normal complete blood count and metabolic panel, while vascular imaging shows no significant occlusive disease in the lower extremities.

A 91-year-old female presents with chronic diarrhea and significant weight loss over the past three months. On physical examination, she has a distended abdomen and signs of malnutrition, including muscle wasting and dry skin. Laboratory tests reveal elevated anti-tissue transglutaminase antibodies and a low hemoglobin level indicating anemia. An upper endoscopy shows villous atrophy in the duodenum, consistent with celiac disease.

A 90-year-old female presents with complaints of increased abdominal girth and easy bruising over the past six months. Physical examination reveals a rounded face, purple striae on the abdomen, and proximal muscle weakness. Laboratory tests show elevated cortisol levels in a 24-hour urine collection and suppressed ACTH levels.

A 74-year-old female presents with recurrent fractures and chronic pain in her lower extremities. Upon physical examination, she displays blue sclera and a history of multiple bone fractures with minimal trauma. X-rays reveal multiple healed fractures and osteopenia. Genetic testing confirms a mutation in the COL1A1 gene, indicative of Osteogenesis imperfecta.

A 93-year-old male presents with dry, scaly skin primarily affecting his lower extremities and trunk, which he reports has worsened over the past year. On physical examination, his skin is noted to be rough, with fine white scales, particularly on the shins and forearms, and he shows no signs of inflammation or infection. A biopsy of the skin reveals a thickened stratum corneum with minimal inflammation, consistent with ichthyosis vulgaris. Laboratory tests show normal serum electrolytes and no signs of systemic disease.

A 116-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of recurrent severe headaches occurring 15 days per month, accompanied by nausea and sensitivity to light. Physical examination reveals tenderness in the pericranial muscles and a normal neurological exam. MRI of the brain shows no acute intracranial pathology, consistent with a diagnosis of chronic migraines.

A 148-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of persistent cough and shortness of breath for the past three days. Physical examination reveals tachypnea, crackles on lung auscultation, and a fever of 102°F. Chest X-ray shows bilateral infiltrates, and rapid influenza diagnostic test is positive for Influenza A.
actual_diagnosis: Pneumonia due to influenza, ICD-10 code J10.1

doctor_vignette: An 84-year-old male presents with complaints of persistent fatigue and weight gain over the past six months. On physical examination, he exhibits dry skin, bradycardia, and a delayed relaxation phase of deep tendon reflexes. Laboratory tests reveal an elevated TSH level of 12 mIU/L and a low free T4 level of 0.7 ng/dL.

A 41-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of sudden, severe pain and swelling in his right big toe, which started overnight. On examination, the toe is erythematous, warm, and exquisitely tender to touch. Serum uric acid levels are found to be elevated at 9.5 mg/dL, and joint aspiration reveals needle-shaped monosodium urate crystals in the synovial fluid.

A 70-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of increasing shortness of breath and a chronic cough that has worsened over the past six months. On physical examination, she exhibits wheezing, decreased breath sounds bilaterally, and use of accessory muscles for breathing. A recent chest X-ray shows hyperinflation of the lungs, and pulmonary function tests reveal a significant reduction in FEV1/FVC ratio, confirming obstructive lung disease.
actual_diagnosis: Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, ICD-10 code J44.9

doctor_vignette: A 104-year-old female presents with acute chest pain radiating to her left arm, accompanied by shortness of breath. Physical examination reveals diaphoresis, tachycardia, and a blood pressure of 90/60 mmHg. An ECG shows ST-segment elevation in the anterior leads, and troponin levels are significantly elevated.
actual_diagnosis: Acute myocardial infarction, ICD-10 code I21.9

doctor_vignette: A 128-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of severe, throbbing headache that has persisted for the last 24 hours. Physical examination reveals no neurological deficits, and vital signs are stable. The patient reports sensitivity to light and sound but denies any visual disturbances. Routine lab tests and a CT scan of the head show no abnormalities.
actual_diagnosis: Migraine without aura, ICD-10 code G43.009

doctor_vignette: A 102-year-old male presents with severe joint pain and stiffness in both hands and knees, worsening in the morning. Physical examination reveals symmetrical swelling and tenderness in the metacarpophalangeal joints and a positive squeeze test. Laboratory tests show elevated rheumatoid factor and anti-CCP antibodies, along with a significantly raised ESR. X-rays demonstrate joint erosion and narrowing of the joint spaces in the affected areas.

A 52-year-old female presents with progressive weakness and tingling in her legs over the past week, which has now ascended to her arms. On physical exam, she demonstrates decreased muscle strength in all four extremities, with absent deep tendon reflexes. A lumbar puncture reveals elevated protein levels in the cerebrospinal fluid with a normal white cell count. Electromyography shows conduction block, supporting the diagnosis.

A 128-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of persistent, itchy, scaly patches on her elbows and knees. Physical examination reveals well-defined erythematous plaques covered with silvery-white scales. No significant findings are noted in laboratory tests, including a complete blood count and metabolic panel. A skin biopsy confirms the diagnosis of psoriasis.

A 25-year-old female presents with severe right upper quadrant pain and nausea after a fatty meal. On physical examination, she exhibits tenderness in the right upper quadrant and a positive Murphy's sign. Laboratory tests reveal elevated white blood cell count and liver function tests, while an abdominal ultrasound shows gallbladder wall thickening and pericholecystic fluid, indicating inflammation.

A 26-year-old male presents with complaints of decreased urine output and fatigue over the past three days. Physical examination reveals mild edema in the lower extremities and a blood pressure of 130/85 mmHg. Laboratory results show elevated serum creatinine levels of 3.5 mg/dL and a BUN of 30 mg/dL, indicating impaired kidney function. Urinalysis reveals muddy brown casts consistent with acute tubular necrosis.
actual_diagnosis: Acute kidney injury, ICD-10 code N17.9

doctor_vignette: A 57-year-old male presents with fatigue and weakness over the past month. On physical examination, he has pale conjunctiva and a mild tachycardia. Laboratory tests reveal a hemoglobin level of 10.2 g/dL, low ferritin at 10 ng/mL, and increased total iron-binding capacity. No recent gastrointestinal bleeding is noted on history.
actual_diagnosis: Anemia due to iron deficiency, ICD-10 code D50.9

doctor_vignette: A 42-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of persistent lower back pain following a minor fall. Physical exam reveals tenderness in the lumbar spine and a noticeable loss of height. Bone density testing indicates a T-score of -2.8, consistent with osteoporosis. She has a history of amenorrhea and low calcium intake, contributing factors to her condition.

A 93-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of worsening tremors in his right hand over the past six months. Physical examination reveals a resting tremor, bradykinesia, and rigidity in his upper extremities, along with a shuffling gait. His Mini-Mental State Examination score is 24, indicating mild cognitive impairment. MRI of the brain shows no acute abnormalities but confirms age-related changes.

An 84-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of persistent cough and unexplained weight loss over the past three months. On physical examination, he has decreased breath sounds in the left lung base and notable lymphadenopathy in the cervical region. Chest X-ray reveals a cavitary lesion in the left upper lobe, and sputum smear shows acid-fast bacilli.

A 100-year-old female presents with worsening muscle weakness, particularly in her eyes and limbs, over the past two months. On examination, she exhibits bilateral ptosis and generalized muscle fatigability. A serological test reveals the presence of acetylcholine receptor antibodies, and a CT scan shows thymic hyperplasia.

A 104-year-old male presents with progressive dyspnea and a persistent dry cough over the past three months. Physical examination reveals diminished breath sounds, clubbing of the fingers, and crackles on lung auscultation. A chest CT scan shows reticular patterns and ground-glass opacities consistent with interstitial lung disease.
actual_diagnosis: Interstitial lung disease, ICD-10 code J84.9

doctor_vignette: A 56-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of a persistent dull headache that has lasted for the past week. On physical examination, she exhibits tenderness in the pericranial muscles and normal neurological findings. No significant abnormalities were noted in her routine blood tests or imaging studies, which were unremarkable. She reports increased stress at work and poor sleep quality, contributing to her symptoms.

A 121-year-old male presents with complaints of increased hand and foot size over the past few years. Physical examination reveals prominent facial features including a protruding jaw, enlarged hands, and thickened skin. Laboratory tests show elevated insulin-like growth factor 1 (IGF-1) levels, and an MRI of the pituitary gland reveals a pituitary adenoma.

A 9-year-old female presents to the clinic with severe abdominal pain and fatigue over the past two days. On physical examination, she exhibits pallor and tenderness in the abdomen, with a heart rate of 110 bpm. A complete blood count reveals a hemoglobin level of 6.5 g/dL and reticulocyte count is elevated. Peripheral blood smear shows sickle-shaped red blood cells.
actual_diagnosis: Sickle cell disease, ICD-10 code D57.9

doctor_vignette: A 69-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of fever and productive cough for the past three days. On physical examination, he has decreased breath sounds and dullness to percussion on the right side, with crackles noted on auscultation. A chest X-ray reveals a right lower lobe consolidation, and sputum culture grows Klebsiella pneumoniae.
actual_diagnosis: Pneumonia due to Klebsiella pneumoniae, ICD-10 code J15.0

doctor_vignette: A 22-year-old male presents with mood swings, reporting episodes of extreme elation followed by deep depressive states. During the physical exam, he exhibits a pressured speech pattern and displays signs of psychomotor agitation. No significant lab abnormalities are noted, and a routine urinalysis is unremarkable. There are no imaging studies performed, but the patient's history reveals recurrent mood episodes over the past year.

A 21-year-old male presents for a routine check-up, reporting fatigue and occasional chest discomfort after exercise. Physical examination reveals a body mass index (BMI) of 28 and xanthomas on his elbows. Lab results show elevated total cholesterol at 290 mg/dL and LDL levels at 180 mg/dL, with a low HDL of 35 mg/dL.

A 105-year-old female presents with complaints of aching and heaviness in her legs, particularly after prolonged sitting. Physical examination reveals prominent, tortuous veins in both lower extremities, with significant edema and skin changes in the affected areas. Doppler ultrasound confirms reflux in the great saphenous vein, indicative of chronic venous insufficiency.
actual_diagnosis: Varicose veins of lower extremities, ICD-10 code I83.90

doctor_vignette: A 142-year-old female presents with recurrent oral ulcers and painful genital lesions. Physical examination reveals erythematous nodules on her lower extremities and signs of uveitis in her left eye. Laboratory tests show elevated inflammatory markers and a positive pathergy test. Imaging of the eyes confirms retinal inflammation.

A 48-year-old male presents with recurrent joint dislocations and chronic joint pain. On physical examination, he demonstrates hypermobility in multiple joints, particularly in the fingers and elbows, alongside skin that is notably elastic and easily bruised. Genetic testing reveals a mutation in the COL5A1 gene, confirming connective tissue disorder.

A 13-year-old male presents with complaints of fatigue and mild abdominal discomfort. On physical examination, he has a slightly enlarged liver and is noted to be overweight with a BMI in the 95th percentile. Laboratory tests reveal elevated liver enzymes (ALT and AST) and an abdominal ultrasound shows hepatic steatosis.
actual_diagnosis: Non-alcoholic fatty liver disease, ICD-10 code K76.0

doctor_vignette: A 148-year-old female presents with complaints of intermittent claudication, experiencing pain in her legs during walking. Physical examination reveals diminished femoral and popliteal pulses, and a notable decrease in ankle-brachial index (ABI) of 0.4. Additionally, her feet appear cold and have a pale coloration. Doppler ultrasound confirms significant stenosis in the superficial femoral artery.
actual_diagnosis: Peripheral artery disease, ICD-10 code I73.9

doctor_vignette: An 84-year-old male presents to the emergency department with palpitations and shortness of breath for the past two days. On examination, he is found to have an irregularly irregular pulse at a rate of 130 beats per minute, along with mild bilateral lower extremity edema. An ECG reveals atrial fibrillation with no acute ischemic changes, and a chest X-ray shows mild cardiomegaly.

A 99-year-old male presents with increased thirst and frequent urination over the past week. Physical exam reveals weight loss and dry mucous membranes. Laboratory tests show a blood glucose level of 350 mg/dL and positive ketones in the urine. A history of early onset diabetes is noted, suggesting Type 1 diabetes mellitus.
actual_diagnosis: Type 1 diabetes mellitus, ICD-10 code E10.9

doctor_vignette: A 130-year-old female presents with complaints of persistent headaches and dizziness over the past month. On physical examination, her blood pressure is recorded at 180/95 mmHg, and she exhibits mild edema in the lower extremities. Laboratory tests show elevated serum creatinine levels at 1.5 mg/dL, indicating possible renal impairment associated with chronic hypertension.

A 102-year-old female presents with severe pain and stiffness in her knees, particularly after prolonged sitting. On physical examination, there is noticeable crepitus and tenderness over the medial joint lines of both knees, with a reduced range of motion. X-rays reveal joint space narrowing and osteophyte formation consistent with osteoarthritis.

A 35-year-old male presents with severe abdominal pain radiating to the back, accompanied by nausea and vomiting. On physical examination, he exhibits tenderness in the upper abdomen and a positive Cullen's sign. Laboratory tests reveal elevated serum amylase and lipase levels, and an abdominal ultrasound shows peritoneal fluid around the pancreas.

A 69-year-old female presents with worsening shortness of breath and wheezing, particularly at night. On examination, she demonstrates decreased breath sounds bilaterally and prolonged expiration with audible wheezing. A peak flow measurement reveals a reading significantly below her personal best, and a chest X-ray shows no acute abnormalities. Her history includes frequent respiratory infections and a recent increase in use of her rescue inhaler.

A 132-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of persistent itchy rash on her arms and legs. Physical examination reveals red, inflamed patches with oozing and crusting, particularly in the antecubital and popliteal fossae. There are no significant laboratory findings, but a skin scrape shows no evidence of fungal infection. The patient has a history of dry skin and has recently changed her soap, which may have triggered her symptoms.

A 6-year-old female presents with recurrent abdominal pain and bloody diarrhea for the past three weeks. On physical examination, she has tenderness in the left lower quadrant and signs of dehydration. Laboratory tests reveal a significantly elevated C-reactive protein and anemia with low hemoglobin levels. Colonoscopy shows superficial ulcers in the colon, consistent with ulcerative colitis.

An 18-year-old male presents with a 2-day history of fever, severe headache, and neck stiffness. On examination, he exhibits photophobia and a positive Brudzinski's sign. Lumbar puncture reveals cloudy cerebrospinal fluid with an elevated white blood cell count, predominantly neutrophils, and positive Gram stain for Streptococcus pneumoniae. Blood cultures confirm the presence of the same organism.

A 105-year-old male presents with swelling and pain in his left leg, which has progressively worsened over the past week. Physical examination reveals significant edema and tenderness in the left calf, with a positive Homan's sign. Ultrasound imaging confirms the presence of a thrombus in the left popliteal vein. Laboratory tests show elevated D-dimer levels, indicating a possible thrombotic event.
actual_diagnosis: Deep vein thrombosis, ICD-10 code I82.90

doctor_vignette: A 96-year-old female presents with severe left lower abdominal pain and light vaginal bleeding. Physical examination reveals tenderness and guarding in the left lower quadrant, with a palpable mass. Transvaginal ultrasound shows an empty uterine cavity and an adnexal mass consistent with an ectopic pregnancy. Serum beta-hCG levels are significantly elevated at 2500 mIU/ml.

A 66-year-old male presents with persistent auditory hallucinations and disorganized speech, stating that he hears voices telling him to harm himself. Physical examination reveals poor hygiene and flattened affect. No significant abnormalities are noted on laboratory tests, and a CT scan of the brain shows no structural lesions.

A 148-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of worsening abdominal pain and a noticeable bulge in the left groin area. Physical examination reveals tenderness and a reducible mass upon palpation, with no signs of incarceration. An abdominal ultrasound shows a left inguinal hernia with no evidence of strangulation.

A 64-year-old female presents with complaints of skin thickening and tightening, particularly on her hands and face, accompanied by Raynaud's phenomenon. Physical examination reveals sclerodactyly, with loss of digital creases and shiny skin on the fingers. Laboratory tests show positive anti-Scl-70 antibodies and elevated erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR).

A 54-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of a noticeable lump in his neck that has increased in size over the past three months. Physical examination reveals a firm, non-tender nodule in the right lobe of the thyroid, along with mild cervical lymphadenopathy. A thyroid ultrasound shows a hypoechoic lesion with irregular margins, and fine-needle aspiration biopsy confirms the presence of malignant cells.

A 150-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of recurrent headaches occurring at least 15 days a month for the past six months. On physical examination, she exhibits tenderness in the pericranial muscles and photophobia. Neurological assessment reveals no focal deficits, and a CT scan of the head is unremarkable, ruling out secondary causes of headache.

A 69-year-old female presents with worsening shortness of breath on exertion and fatigue over the past few months. Physical examination reveals elevated jugular venous pressure, a loud P2 heart sound, and peripheral edema. A right heart catheterization shows a mean pulmonary artery pressure of 40 mmHg, confirming the diagnosis.

A 109-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of persistent ringing in his ears for the past month, which has been interfering with his sleep. On physical examination, there is slight cerumen impaction noted in both ears, but no signs of infection. Audiometry reveals a significant sensorineural hearing loss bilaterally, consistent with age-related changes. No acute abnormalities were found on CT imaging of the temporal bones.

A 51-year-old female presents to the emergency department with a chief complaint of experiencing recurrent seizures over the past month. Physical examination reveals postictal confusion and a slight tongue laceration. An EEG shows generalized spike-and-wave discharges consistent with epilepsy, while a CT scan of the head is unremarkable.

A 116-year-old male presents with persistent abdominal pain and diarrhea for the past three weeks. Physical examination reveals tenderness in the lower abdomen and signs of malnutrition. Laboratory tests show elevated inflammatory markers and a colonoscopy indicates segmental inflammation consistent with Crohn's disease.

A 129-year-old female presents with fatigue and shortness of breath on exertion. Physical examination reveals pale conjunctiva and a heart rate of 110 bpm. Laboratory tests show a hemoglobin level of 8.5 g/dL, low serum ferritin, and low transferrin saturation, indicating iron deficiency.
actual_diagnosis: Iron deficiency anemia, ICD-10 code D50.9

doctor_vignette: An 86-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of unusual vaginal discharge and a fishy odor for the past week. Physical examination reveals a thin, grayish-white discharge and mild vulvar irritation. A wet mount shows a decrease in lactobacilli and an increase in clue cells. The pH of the vaginal discharge is measured at 5.5, confirming the diagnosis.

A 7-year-old male presents with complaints of persistent fatigue and difficulty breathing during play. On physical examination, he exhibits tachycardia, bilateral pitting edema, and a heart murmur. Chest X-ray reveals cardiomegaly, and an echocardiogram shows left ventricular dysfunction. Laboratory tests indicate elevated B-type natriuretic peptide (BNP) levels, confirming heart failure.

A 121-year-old male presents with fatigue and palpitations. Physical exam reveals an irregular heart rhythm and mild splenomegaly. Laboratory tests show elevated cardiac enzymes and serology positive for Trypanosoma cruzi. Chest X-ray indicates cardiomegaly.

A 91-year-old female presents with complaints of eye strain and fatigue after reading for short periods. On examination, she demonstrates reduced visual acuity of 20/40 in both eyes, with no significant findings on a dilated fundoscopic exam. The patient reports difficulty focusing on close objects and experiences headaches in the brow region. Refraction testing reveals a need for updated prescription glasses, indicating presbyopia as a contributing factor.

An 82-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of severe agitation and confusion. On examination, she is febrile with a temperature of 104°F, tachycardic with a heart rate of 140 bpm, and exhibits tremors in her hands. Laboratory results reveal elevated free T4 levels at 4.5 ng/dL and a suppressed TSH level of <0.01 µIU/mL, consistent with thyrotoxicosis.

A 124-year-old male presents with recurrent episodes of vertigo lasting up to an hour, accompanied by tinnitus and fluctuating hearing loss. On examination, he exhibits positive Romberg sign and nystagmus. Audiometry reveals a sensorineural hearing loss pattern. MRI of the brain shows no structural abnormalities, ruling out other causes of his symptoms.

A 113-year-old female presents with acute abdominal pain localized to the right lower quadrant, accompanied by nausea and vomiting for the past 12 hours. Physical examination reveals tenderness and guarding in the right lower abdomen, with a fever of 101°F. Laboratory tests show elevated white blood cell count at 15,000/mm³, and an abdominal ultrasound reveals an enlarged, non-compressible appendix consistent with acute appendicitis.

A 114-year-old male presented with sudden onset shortness of breath and chest pain. Physical exam revealed tachycardia, hypoxia, and unilateral leg swelling. A CT pulmonary angiogram showed an occlusion in the right pulmonary artery. D-dimer levels were significantly elevated.

An 18-year-old female presents for a routine check-up and reports occasional headaches and dizziness. Her blood pressure is measured at 150/95 mmHg, and she has a BMI in the overweight range. A urinalysis shows no abnormalities, and laboratory tests reveal normal renal function and electrolyte levels.

A 35-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of intermittent numbness and tingling in her right arm and leg over the past month. Neurological examination reveals weakness in the right upper and lower extremities, along with a positive Babinski sign. MRI of the brain shows multiple hyperintense lesions in the periventricular white matter consistent with demyelination.

A 6-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of persistent cough and wheezing, worsening with physical activity. On physical examination, she exhibits prolonged expiratory phase, decreased breath sounds bilaterally, and uses accessory muscles for breathing. A chest X-ray shows hyperinflation of the lungs, and spirometry reveals an obstructive pattern with a reduced FEV1/FVC ratio, consistent with chronic airway obstruction.
actual_diagnosis: 4. Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, ICD-10 code J44.9

doctor_vignette: An 87-year-old female presents with increased thirst and frequent urination over the past month. Physical examination reveals a BMI of 32, dry mucous membranes, and decreased sensation in her feet. Laboratory tests show HbA1c of 8.5% and fasting glucose level of 180 mg/dL, indicating poorly controlled blood sugar levels.
actual_diagnosis: 6. Type 2 diabetes mellitus, ICD-10 code E11.9

doctor_vignette: A 103-year-old male presents with worsening shortness of breath and wheezing over the past week. Physical examination reveals prolonged expiratory phase and bilateral wheezing on auscultation. A peak flow measurement shows a reading significantly below his baseline, and a chest X-ray shows hyperinflation of the lungs but no acute infiltrates.

An 80-year-old female presents with persistent cough and recurrent respiratory infections. Physical examination reveals digital clubbing and wheezing on auscultation. Chest X-ray shows bronchiectasis, and sputum culture grows Pseudomonas aeruginosa. Sweat chloride test returns elevated levels, confirming a diagnosis consistent with cystic fibrosis.

A 61-year-old female presents with persistent shortness of breath and swelling in her legs. On physical exam, she has elevated jugular venous pressure, bilateral pedal edema, and crackles on lung auscultation. An echocardiogram reveals a reduced ejection fraction of 35%, and a BNP level is significantly elevated at 800 pg/mL.
actual_diagnosis: 11. Congestive heart failure, ICD-10 code I50.9

doctor_vignette: An 8-year-old female presents with complaints of fatigue and weight gain despite a normal appetite. Physical examination reveals dry skin, thinning hair, and bradycardia. Laboratory tests show elevated TSH levels and low free T4, indicating hypothyroidism.

A 9-year-old male presents with abdominal pain and diarrhea lasting for two weeks. On examination, he has tenderness in the right lower quadrant and appears to have lost weight. Laboratory tests reveal anemia with low hemoglobin levels and elevated inflammatory markers. An abdominal ultrasound shows thickening of the ileal wall, suggesting possible Crohn's disease.

A 96-year-old male presents with increasing social withdrawal and auditory hallucinations, stating he hears voices that tell him to harm himself. Physical examination reveals a flat affect and disorganized thinking, with no acute medical issues noted. MRI of the brain shows age-related changes but no acute intracranial abnormalities, and routine lab tests are within normal limits. These findings are consistent with a diagnosis of schizophrenia.

A 149-year-old male presents with severe pain and swelling in his right big toe, which began suddenly two days ago. On examination, the affected joint is erythematous and tender to touch, with limited range of motion. Serum uric acid levels are significantly elevated at 9.5 mg/dL, and a joint aspiration reveals needle-shaped monosodium urate crystals.

A 67-year-old male presents with persistent knee pain, particularly during weight-bearing activities. On physical examination, there is tenderness and swelling around the medial aspect of the right knee, with reduced range of motion and crepitus noted during flexion and extension. X-rays reveal joint space narrowing and osteophyte formation consistent with osteoarthritis.

An 18-year-old female presents with joint pain and fatigue for the past month. On physical exam, she has a facial rash resembling a butterfly distribution across her cheeks, and her joints exhibit swelling and tenderness. Laboratory tests reveal a positive antinuclear antibody (ANA) test and elevated anti-double-stranded DNA antibodies, consistent with autoimmune activity.
actual_diagnosis: 15. Systemic lupus erythematosus, ICD-10 code M32.9

doctor_vignette: A 19-year-old male presents to the emergency department with palpitations and shortness of breath that began suddenly while playing basketball. Physical examination reveals an irregularly irregular pulse at a rate of 150 beats per minute and mild bilateral edema in the lower extremities. An ECG shows atrial fibrillation with rapid ventricular response, and a chest X-ray is unremarkable.

An 11-year-old male presents with recurrent fevers and lymphadenopathy over the past month. On physical examination, notable cervical lymphadenopathy and splenomegaly are observed. Laboratory tests reveal elevated inflammatory markers and positive cultures for non-tuberculous mycobacteria. Genetic testing confirms a mutation associated with Mendelian susceptibility to mycobacterial disease.
actual_diagnosis: 16. Mendelian susceptibility to mycobacterial disease, ICD-10 code D84.81

doctor_vignette: A 20-year-old female presents with severe abdominal pain radiating to her back, accompanied by nausea and vomiting for the past 24 hours. On physical examination, she exhibits tenderness in the epigastric region and signs of guarding. Laboratory tests reveal elevated serum amylase and lipase levels, and an abdominal ultrasound shows peritoneal fluid but no gallstones.

A 69-year-old male presents with chronic blistering and erosions on the skin, predominantly on the hands and forearms, which have worsened over the past year. Physical examination reveals fragile, blistered skin with scarring and thickening in areas of trauma. A skin biopsy shows a separation of the epidermis from the dermis, confirming the diagnosis. Genetic testing reveals mutations in the COL7A1 gene, consistent with dystrophic epidermolysis bullosa.

A 56-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of unintentional weight loss and increased anxiety over the past three months. On physical examination, he exhibits tachycardia, tremors in his hands, and a noticeable goiter. Laboratory results reveal elevated free T4 and suppressed TSH levels, confirming hyperthyroidism.

An 84-year-old male presents with persistent fatigue and unexplained weight loss over the past three months. Physical examination reveals cervical lymphadenopathy and splenomegaly. A CT scan shows enlarged mediastinal lymph nodes, and a biopsy confirms Reed-Sternberg cells. Blood tests indicate elevated lactate dehydrogenase (LDH) levels.

A 102-year-old male presents with increasing memory loss and confusion over the past 6 months. Physical examination reveals disorientation to time and place, and he is unable to recall recent events. Neurological assessment shows mild aphasia and impaired short-term memory. MRI of the brain indicates general cerebral atrophy, consistent with dementia.

A 143-year-old male presents with excessive daytime sleepiness and sudden episodes of muscle weakness triggered by laughter. Physical examination reveals normal neurological function with no signs of other sleep disorders. Polysomnography shows reduced REM latency and multiple sleep-onset REM periods, confirming the diagnosis.

A 133-year-old male presents with fatigue and muscle weakness. Physical examination reveals xanthomas on the elbows and knees, indicative of lipid accumulation. Laboratory results show elevated total cholesterol of 320 mg/dL and triglycerides of 250 mg/dL. These findings are consistent with significant dyslipidemia.

A 44-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of high fever and severe joint pain for the past three days. On examination, she has a temperature of 102°F, notable swelling in her hands and wrists, and a rash on her trunk. Laboratory tests reveal elevated liver enzymes and a positive serology for Chikungunya virus.

A 141-year-old male presents with fatigue and recurrent infections over the past month. Physical examination reveals pallor, splenomegaly, and petechiae on the lower extremities. Complete blood count shows leukocytosis with 80% lymphoblasts and thrombocytopenia. Bone marrow biopsy confirms the diagnosis of acute lymphoblastic leukemia.
actual_diagnosis: Acute lymphoblastic leukemia, ICD-10 code C91.0

doctor_vignette: A 101-year-old male presents with persistent fatigue and unexplained bruising. On examination, he exhibits pallor and splenomegaly. Laboratory results reveal leukocytosis with a predominance of blast cells and thrombocytopenia. A bone marrow biopsy confirms the presence of acute leukemia.

A 43-year-old male presents to the emergency department with sudden onset of severe chest and back pain, described as tearing in nature. On physical examination, he has a pronounced pulse in the abdomen and a blood pressure of 80/50 mmHg. A chest X-ray shows a widened mediastinum, and a CT scan confirms the presence of an aortic aneurysm measuring 5.5 cm in diameter.

A 131-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of increasing difficulty with movement and tremors in her right hand. On physical examination, she exhibits bradykinesia, a resting tremor, and rigidity in the limbs. A recent MRI shows mild cortical atrophy without acute intracranial abnormalities. Lab tests reveal normal levels of thyroid function and no signs of metabolic disorders.

A 124-year-old female presents with progressive cognitive decline and tremors. On physical examination, she exhibits a mask-like facial expression and Kayser-Fleischer rings in her corneas. Laboratory tests reveal elevated serum copper levels and low ceruloplasmin. MRI of the brain shows basal ganglia hyperintensities consistent with Wilson's disease.

A 122-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of worsening shortness of breath and cough for the past three days. Physical examination reveals decreased breath sounds and dullness to percussion in the right lower lung field. Chest X-ray shows right lower lobe consolidation, and sputum culture is positive for Streptococcus pneumoniae.
actual_diagnosis: Pneumonia due to Streptococcus pneumoniae, ICD-10 code J18.0

doctor_vignette: A 148-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of persistent facial acne and lesions for the past six months. On physical examination, there are multiple comedones, papules, and pustules primarily on the face, particularly on the forehead and cheeks. No systemic abnormalities are noted, and laboratory tests reveal normal hormone levels, ruling out secondary causes of acne.

A 22-year-old female presents with persistent fatigue and unexplained weight loss over the past month. On physical exam, notable findings include lymphadenopathy in the cervical and axillary regions. Laboratory tests reveal elevated lactate dehydrogenase (LDH) levels and a biopsy of the enlarged lymph nodes shows atypical lymphoid cells. CT imaging of the chest and abdomen shows multiple enlarged lymph nodes, consistent with lymphoma.

A 144-year-old female presents with severe left lower quadrant abdominal pain and fever. On physical examination, she exhibits tenderness and guarding in the left lower abdomen. A CT scan of the abdomen reveals multiple diverticula with associated inflammation and thickening of the colonic wall. Laboratory tests show an elevated white blood cell count indicating infection.

A 60-year-old female presents with progressive muscle weakness, particularly in her lower extremities, leading to difficulty walking. Physical examination reveals significant muscle atrophy in the proximal muscles and diminished deep tendon reflexes. Electromyography shows signs of neurogenic changes, and genetic testing confirms a deletion in the SMN1 gene.
actual_diagnosis: Spinal muscular atrophy, ICD-10 code G12.0

doctor_vignette: A 13-year-old male presents with increased thirst, frequent urination, and fatigue for the past month. Physical exam reveals obesity with a BMI in the 95th percentile, and acanthosis nigricans on his neck. Laboratory tests show an elevated fasting blood glucose level of 180 mg/dL and HbA1c of 7.2%.
actual_diagnosis: Diabetes mellitus type 2, ICD-10 code E11.9

doctor_vignette: A 131-year-old male presented with a chief complaint of fever and increased shortness of breath for three days. Physical examination revealed decreased breath sounds and crackles upon auscultation, along with a temperature of 102°F. A chest X-ray showed bilateral infiltrates, and sputum culture confirmed the presence of Streptococcus pneumoniae.

A 23-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of severe fatigue and petechial rash on her lower extremities. Physical examination reveals pallor and mucosal bleeding. Laboratory tests show a markedly low platelet count of 20,000/µL, elevated lactate dehydrogenase (LDH) levels, and a negative direct Coombs test, suggesting microangiopathic hemolytic anemia.
actual_diagnosis: Thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura, ICD-10 code D68.4

doctor_vignette: An 113-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of persistent joint pain and stiffness, particularly in the hands and knees. Physical examination reveals swollen, tender metacarpophalangeal joints and a decreased range of motion in the affected areas. Laboratory tests show elevated rheumatoid factor and anti-CCP antibodies, along with anemia and elevated ESR.

A 116-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of unintentional weight loss and increased appetite over the past month. Physical examination reveals tremors in the hands, a rapid heartbeat at 110 beats per minute, and warm, moist skin. Thyroid function tests show elevated free T4 and suppressed TSH levels, confirming hyperthyroidism.

A 127-year-old male presents with recurrent, severe facial pain described as electric shocks on the right side of his face, lasting seconds to minutes. Physical examination reveals tenderness along the right maxillary and mandibular branches of the trigeminal nerve, with no neurological deficits. MRI of the brain shows vascular compression of the trigeminal nerve root entry zone.

A 148-year-old female presents with recurrent episodes of intense fear, accompanied by palpitations, shortness of breath, and dizziness. Physical examination reveals mild tachycardia and normal respiratory effort, with no signs of acute distress. Laboratory tests, including a complete blood count and metabolic panel, are unremarkable, ruling out other causes of her symptoms.

A 102-year-old female presents to the emergency department with severe right upper quadrant abdominal pain and fever. On physical examination, she exhibits tenderness and guarding in the right upper quadrant, with a positive Murphy's sign. Laboratory tests reveal leukocytosis with a white blood cell count of 15,000/mm³, and an abdominal ultrasound shows a thickened gallbladder wall with pericholecystic fluid, indicative of acute cholecystitis.

A 21-year-old female presents with excessive daytime sleepiness and episodes of sudden muscle weakness triggered by laughter. Physical examination reveals a normal neurological assessment, with no signs of other sleep disorders. A polysomnography shows decreased REM latency and multiple sleep-onset REM periods, confirming her symptoms.

An 8-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of high fever and lethargy for two days. On examination, she is febrile at 39.5°C, tachycardic, and exhibits signs of dehydration with dry mucous membranes. Laboratory tests reveal leukocytosis with a white blood cell count of 18,000/mm³ and elevated lactate levels of 4.5 mmol/L, indicating possible septic shock.

A 77-year-old female presents with chronic lower back pain and stiffness, particularly in the morning. Physical examination reveals restricted lumbar spine mobility and tenderness over the sacroiliac joints. Imaging shows bilateral sacroiliitis on X-ray. Laboratory tests indicate elevated inflammatory markers, including ESR and CRP.

A 20-year-old female presents with recurrent episodes of severe headaches, palpitations, and sweating. On physical examination, her blood pressure is noted to be 180/110 mmHg, and she has a heart rate of 120 beats per minute. Urine tests reveal elevated levels of catecholamines and metanephrines, while an abdominal CT scan shows a 3 cm adrenal mass consistent with a pheochromocytoma.

An 18-year-old female presents with severe pain in her chest and back, rated 8/10. On physical exam, she exhibits pallor and tenderness in her abdomen, with decreased breath sounds bilaterally. Laboratory tests reveal a hemoglobin level of 6.5 g/dL and a peripheral blood smear shows sickle-shaped red blood cells.
actual_diagnosis: Sickle cell disease, ICD-10 code D57.0

doctor_vignette: An 85-year-old male presents with social withdrawal and difficulty in understanding social cues. On physical exam, he demonstrates rigid body posture and limited eye contact, consistent with his lifelong pattern of behavior. He reports a keen interest in specific topics but struggles with initiating conversations. No critical lab or imaging results are applicable as this is a developmental disorder diagnosis.

A 10-year-old female presents with complaints of frequent headaches and difficulty with vision. On physical examination, she is noted to have long fingers and toes (arachnodactyly), a tall stature, and a scoliosis deformity. An echocardiogram reveals dilation of the aortic root, consistent with connective tissue disorder.

A 104-year-old male presented to the clinic with increased thirst and frequent urination over the past month. Physical examination revealed a BMI of 28, and he was noted to have dry mucous membranes and decreased skin turgor. Laboratory tests indicated a fasting blood glucose level of 210 mg/dL and HbA1c of 8.2%.
actual_diagnosis: Type 2 diabetes mellitus, ICD-10 code E11.9

doctor_vignette: A 104-year-old female presents with persistent knee pain, exacerbated by movement and relieved by rest. On physical examination, there is notable crepitus and tenderness over the bilateral knees, with decreased range of motion. X-rays reveal joint space narrowing and osteophyte formation, consistent with degenerative changes. No inflammatory markers are elevated in her lab results.

A 134-year-old female presents with a complaint of a palpable swelling in her neck that has gradually increased over the past few months. On physical examination, a firm, non-tender nodule is noted on the right lobe of the thyroid, measuring approximately 2 cm. Ultrasound reveals a solid, hypoechoic nodule with microcalcifications. Thyroid function tests show normal TSH and free T4 levels.

A 94-year-old female presents to the emergency department with chest pain radiating to her left arm and shortness of breath. On examination, she is diaphoretic, with a heart rate of 110 bpm and blood pressure of 90/60 mmHg. ECG shows ST-segment elevation in leads II, III, and aVF, and troponin levels are markedly elevated. Her medical history includes hypertension and hyperlipidemia.

A 27-year-old female presents with unilateral swelling and pain in her left leg, which has been worsening over the past three days. Physical examination reveals significant edema, tenderness along the left calf, and a positive Homan's sign. Doppler ultrasound of the left leg shows a thrombus in the popliteal vein, confirming the diagnosis.
actual_diagnosis: Deep vein thrombosis, ICD-10 code I82.409

doctor_vignette: A 64-year-old male presents with muscle cramps and tingling sensations in his fingers. On physical exam, he demonstrates Chvostek's sign and Trousseau's sign, indicating neuromuscular excitability. Laboratory results reveal a low serum calcium level of 7.5 mg/dL and an elevated serum phosphate level of 5.5 mg/dL, consistent with hypoparathyroidism.

A 127-year-old male presents with gradual loss of peripheral vision and intermittent headaches. On examination, his intraocular pressure is found to be elevated at 28 mmHg, with a notable cupping of the optic disc. Visual field testing reveals significant loss in the peripheral fields, consistent with glaucomatous changes. No other ocular abnormalities were noted during the slit-lamp examination.

A 74-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of persistent heartburn and regurgitation occurring several times a week. On physical examination, she exhibits mild epigastric tenderness and no signs of abdominal distension. An upper gastrointestinal endoscopy reveals esophagitis consistent with gastroesophageal reflux disease. A pH monitoring study confirms abnormal acid exposure in the esophagus.
actual_diagnosis: Acid reflux disease (GERD), ICD-10 code K21.9

doctor_vignette: A 44-year-old male presents with progressive weakness and atrophy of the distal muscles in both legs, making it difficult for him to walk. On examination, there is notable foot drop and a high-arched foot deformity, along with decreased sensation in the lower extremities. Nerve conduction studies reveal slowed conduction velocities in the peroneal and tibial nerves, consistent with a hereditary neuropathy.

A 16-year-old female presents with increased thirst, frequent urination, and unintentional weight loss over the past month. On physical exam, she is noted to have dry mucous membranes and abdominal tenderness. A random blood glucose level is measured at 350 mg/dL, and ketones are detected in her urine.
actual_diagnosis: Diabetes mellitus type 1, ICD-10 code E10.9

doctor_vignette: A 36-year-old male presents with infertility and decreased libido. Physical examination reveals tall stature, gynecomastia, and reduced testicular volume. Laboratory tests show low testosterone levels and elevated luteinizing hormone (LH) and follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH), suggestive of primary testicular failure.

A 96-year-old female presents with sudden onset of right-sided weakness and difficulty speaking. On physical examination, she exhibits right-sided hemiparesis and expressive aphasia. A CT scan of the head shows an area of hypodensity in the left hemisphere, suggesting an ischemic stroke. Laboratory results reveal elevated D-dimer levels, indicating a possible thromboembolic event.
actual_diagnosis: Acute ischemic stroke, ICD-10 code I63.9

doctor_vignette: A 126-year-old male presents to the emergency department with chief complaints of difficulty breathing, swelling of the lips, and hives after eating shrimp for the first time. Physical exam reveals pronounced respiratory distress, wheezing, and diffuse urticaria. Vital signs show hypotension with a blood pressure of 70/40 mmHg and a heart rate of 120 bpm. Laboratory results indicate elevated tryptase levels and low oxygen saturation at 85%.

A 75-year-old male presents with progressive blurred vision and increased sensitivity to light over the past year. On examination, there is notable corneal thinning and a conical protrusion of the cornea, along with irregular astigmatism. Topography imaging reveals a steepening of the inferior cornea, consistent with keratoconus.

An 8-year-old female presents with complaints of persistent fatigue and difficulty breathing during physical activities. On examination, she has bilateral lower extremity edema and a rapid heart rate. Chest X-ray shows cardiomegaly and pulmonary congestion. Laboratory tests reveal elevated B-type natriuretic peptide (BNP) levels, indicating heart strain.
actual_diagnosis: Congestive heart failure, ICD-10 code I50.9

doctor_vignette: A 135-year-old female presents with severe shortness of breath and a productive cough lasting for two weeks. On physical examination, she is tachypneic, with bilateral crackles and decreased breath sounds. Chest X-ray reveals bilateral infiltrates consistent with pneumonia, and her white blood cell count is elevated at 15,000 cells/mm³.

An 87-year-old female presents with severe fatigue and intermittent joint pain in her hands and knees. On physical examination, she demonstrates pallor and has swollen, painful joints. Laboratory results reveal a hemoglobin level of 8.5 g/dL with sickled cells observed on the peripheral blood smear, confirming the diagnosis.
actual_diagnosis: Sickle cell disease, ICD-10 code D57.1

doctor_vignette: A 144-year-old female presents with fatigue and jaundice. On physical examination, she exhibits scleral icterus and hepatomegaly. Laboratory tests reveal elevated liver enzymes (ALT 150 U/L, AST 180 U/L) and a positive hepatitis C antibody test. Ultrasound shows mild hepatic steatosis.

A 44-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of unexplained weight gain and fatigue over the past six months. On physical examination, she exhibits a rounded face, thinning skin with easy bruising, and abdominal striae. Laboratory tests reveal elevated serum cortisol levels and a 24-hour urinary free cortisol test shows increased cortisol excretion, indicating hypercortisolism.

A 65-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of widespread musculoskeletal pain lasting for over three months. On physical examination, she exhibits tenderness in multiple trigger points, including the neck, shoulders, and lower back, along with fatigue and sleep disturbances. Laboratory tests show normal complete blood count, metabolic panel, and inflammatory markers, ruling out other conditions.

A 46-year-old female presents with fatigue, pallor, and recurrent infections over the past month. Physical examination reveals marked pallor, petechiae on her extremities, and a heart rate of 110 bpm. Complete blood count shows severe anemia with hemoglobin at 7 g/dL, leukopenia with a white blood cell count of 2,000/mm³, and thrombocytopenia with a platelet count of 30,000/mm³, indicating bone marrow failure.

A 37-year-old female presents with a 5-day history of high fever, conjunctival injection, and a rash. Physical examination reveals cervical lymphadenopathy and cracked, swollen lips. Laboratory tests show elevated inflammatory markers with a markedly elevated C-reactive protein (CRP) level, and echocardiogram indicates coronary artery dilation.

A 95-year-old male presents with fever, night sweats, and significant fatigue lasting for two weeks. Physical examination reveals splenomegaly and tenderness in the lower abdomen. Blood cultures are positive for Brucella species, and serology shows elevated anti-Brucella antibodies. The patient has a history of exposure to unpasteurized dairy products.

A 71-year-old male presents with persistent dry cough and shortness of breath over the past month. Physical examination reveals bilateral hilar lymphadenopathy and diffuse crackles on lung auscultation. Chest X-ray shows enlarged hilar lymph nodes, and serum angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) levels are elevated, supporting the diagnosis.

A 48-year-old male presents with fatigue, recurrent infections, and easy bruising over the past month. Physical examination reveals pallor, petechiae, and splenomegaly. Complete blood count shows leukocytosis with 60% myeloblasts and thrombocytopenia. Bone marrow biopsy confirms the presence of acute myeloid leukemia.
actual_diagnosis: Acute myeloid leukemia, ICD-10 code C92.0

doctor_vignette: A 94-year-old male presents with a persistent high fever lasting over five days, accompanied by a rash and conjunctivitis. Physical examination reveals cervical lymphadenopathy and cracked lips. Laboratory tests show elevated inflammatory markers and a notable thrombocytosis, while echocardiogram indicates coronary artery dilation.

A 46-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of worsening cough and fever for three days. On examination, she exhibits decreased breath sounds and dullness to percussion in the right lower lung field. Chest X-ray reveals a right lower lobe infiltrate, and a sputum culture confirms the presence of Streptococcus pneumoniae.
actual_diagnosis: Pneumonia due to Streptococcus pneumoniae, ICD-10 code J18.9

doctor_vignette: A 38-year-old female presents with fatigue and persistent lower back pain. On physical examination, she has mild edema in her lower extremities and palpable tenderness in the bilateral flank areas. Laboratory tests reveal an elevated serum creatinine level of 2.1 mg/dL and a glomerular filtration rate (GFR) of 45 mL/min, indicating a decline in kidney function.
actual_diagnosis: Chronic kidney disease stage 3, ICD-10 code N18.3

doctor_vignette: A 23-year-old male presents to the emergency department with difficulty breathing and extensive hives after eating shellfish for the first time. On physical examination, he is noted to have angioedema of the lips and tongue, wheezing, and a blood pressure of 90/60 mmHg. Initial lab results show elevated serum tryptase levels consistent with anaphylaxis.
actual_diagnosis: Severe allergic reaction, ICD-10 code T78.2

doctor_vignette: A 59-year-old male presents with complaints of excessive daytime sleepiness and loud snoring, reported by his partner. On physical examination, he has a body mass index of 32, a thick neck circumference of 18 inches, and exhibits signs of fatigue. A polysomnography reveals multiple episodes of apnea and hypopnea throughout the night, confirming the diagnosis.
actual_diagnosis: Obstructive sleep apnea, ICD-10 code G47.33

doctor_vignette: An 85-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of persistent cough and unintentional weight loss over the past month. On physical examination, she exhibits decreased breath sounds in the right upper lung field and crackles upon auscultation. A chest X-ray reveals a cavitary lesion in the right upper lobe, and sputum analysis is positive for Mycobacterium tuberculosis.
actual_diagnosis: Tuberculosis of the lung, ICD-10 code A15.0

doctor_vignette: A 113-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of persistent pelvic pain and frequent urination, experiencing urgency with minimal urine output. Physical examination reveals tenderness in the suprapubic area and no abnormalities in the genitalia. Urinalysis shows no signs of infection, while cystoscopy reveals bladder wall inflammation and glomerulations, consistent with interstitial cystitis.

An 88-year-old female presents to the emergency department with sudden onset of severe headache and right-sided weakness. On physical examination, she exhibits right-sided hemiparesis and expressive aphasia. A CT scan of the head reveals a large intracerebral hemorrhage in the left hemisphere. Laboratory tests show normal coagulation profile.

A 29-year-old female presents with persistent fatigue, weight loss, and increased pigmentation of her skin. On physical examination, she has low blood pressure and hyperkalemia is noted on lab results, along with low cortisol levels. The ACTH stimulation test confirms adrenal insufficiency.

A 77-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of increasing discomfort due to multiple skin lesions. Physical examination reveals numerous café-au-lait spots and neurofibromas on his trunk and extremities. MRI of the brain shows no evidence of tumors, but there are indications of plexiform neurofibromas in the cervical region. Family history is notable for similar skin findings in relatives, suggesting a genetic predisposition.

A 124-year-old male presents with increased thirst and frequent urination over the past month. Physical examination reveals obesity with a BMI of 32, and a foot exam shows slight neuropathy. Laboratory tests indicate an HbA1c of 8.5% and fasting glucose of 180 mg/dL, confirming poor glycemic control.
actual_diagnosis: 4. Diabetes mellitus type 2, ICD-10 code E11.9

doctor_vignette: A 31-year-old female presents with increasing shortness of breath and a persistent cough over the past six months. On physical examination, she has wheezing and decreased breath sounds bilaterally, along with mild jaundice. A serum alpha-1 antitrypsin level is found to be significantly low, and a CT scan of the chest shows emphysematous changes in the lower lobes.
actual_diagnosis: Alpha-1 antitrypsin deficiency, ICD-10 code E88.01

doctor_vignette: A 107-year-old female presents to the emergency department with acute chest pain and shortness of breath. On examination, she exhibits diaphoresis, tachycardia, and a blood pressure of 90/60 mmHg. An ECG reveals ST-segment elevation in the inferior leads, and cardiac troponin levels are significantly elevated.
actual_diagnosis: 5. Acute myocardial infarction, ICD-10 code I21.9

doctor_vignette: A 10-year-old female presents with recurrent abdominal pain, diarrhea, and significant weight loss over the past six months. Physical examination reveals a distended abdomen and signs of malnutrition, including pallor and delayed growth. Serological tests show elevated tissue transglutaminase (tTG) antibodies and a confirmatory duodenal biopsy indicates villous atrophy.

A 14-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of persistent cough and shortness of breath, particularly during physical activities. On examination, he has diminished breath sounds and wheezing bilaterally, with a prolonged expiratory phase noted. A chest X-ray reveals hyperinflated lungs, and spirometry shows a reduced FEV1/FVC ratio consistent with obstructive lung disease.
actual_diagnosis: 6. Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, ICD-10 code J44.9

doctor_vignette: A 49-year-old female presents with complaints of unintentional weight loss, increased anxiety, and palpitations over the past few months. On physical examination, she exhibits a fine tremor in her hands, a rapid heart rate of 110 bpm, and noticeable enlargement of the thyroid gland. Laboratory tests reveal elevated free T4 and suppressed TSH levels, confirming the diagnosis.

A 51-year-old female presents with persistent pain and stiffness in her right knee, particularly after prolonged sitting or activity. On physical examination, there is tenderness over the medial joint line, and the knee shows decreased range of motion with crepitus noted during flexion and extension. X-rays reveal joint space narrowing and osteophyte formation, confirming the diagnosis.
actual_diagnosis: 7. Osteoarthritis of knee, ICD-10 code M17.9

doctor_vignette: A 132-year-old female presents with persistent fatigue and a rash on her face that resembles a butterfly pattern across her cheeks. Physical examination reveals joint swelling in her hands and signs of pleuritis. Laboratory tests show positive anti-nuclear antibodies (ANA) and a low complement level, indicative of autoimmune activity.
actual_diagnosis: 10. Systemic lupus erythematosus, ICD-10 code M32.9

doctor_vignette: A 1-year-old male presents with sudden onset of severe chest and back pain, accompanied by vomiting. On examination, he has a weak pulse in the right arm compared to the left, and a blood pressure differential of 20 mmHg between the arms. A chest X-ray reveals a widened mediastinum, and a subsequent echocardiogram shows evidence of aortic dissection.

A 40-year-old female presents with recurrent episodes of staring and unresponsiveness lasting about 1-2 minutes over the past month. Physical examination reveals no focal neurological deficits, but the patient appears confused after each episode. An EEG shows generalized spike-and-wave activity consistent with epileptic seizures, and a brain MRI is unremarkable.

An 8-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of itchy, scaly patches on her elbows and knees that have persisted for several weeks. Physical examination reveals well-defined, erythematous plaques covered with silvery scales in typical locations. There is no evidence of secondary infection, and laboratory tests show no abnormalities in inflammatory markers. Family history is significant for psoriasis in her mother.

A 60-year-old female presents with a persistent productive cough and increased shortness of breath over the past few months. Physical examination reveals digital clubbing and wheezing on auscultation. Chest X-ray shows bronchiectasis, and sputum culture is positive for Pseudomonas aeruginosa, indicating chronic lung infection.

A 2-year-old male presents with intermittent episodes of weakness, particularly in the arms and legs, which worsen with activity and improve with rest. On examination, he exhibits noticeable ptosis and generalized muscle fatigue, especially after prolonged play. A repetitive nerve stimulation test shows a decremental response, and serum anti-acetylcholine receptor antibodies are elevated. These findings are suggestive of myasthenia gravis in this young patient.

An 111-year-old male presents with progressive muscle weakness and difficulty swallowing over the past six months. Physical examination reveals fasciculations in the tongue and atrophy of the upper extremities. Neurological assessment shows brisk deep tendon reflexes and a positive Babinski sign. Electromyography confirms widespread denervation and reinnervation patterns consistent with amyotrophic lateral sclerosis.
actual_diagnosis: 18. Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, ICD-10 code G12.21

doctor_vignette: A 24-year-old male presents with progressive weakness in his lower extremities over the past week, accompanied by tingling and numbness. On examination, he exhibits decreased deep tendon reflexes and muscle weakness, particularly in the proximal muscles. A lumbar puncture reveals elevated protein levels with normal white cell counts in the cerebrospinal fluid, consistent with Guillain-Barré syndrome.

A 121-year-old male presents with severe fatigue and intermittent pain crises in his joints. Physical examination reveals pallor, jaundice, and swollen hands. Laboratory tests show a hemoglobin level of 6.5 g/dL with significant sickle-shaped cells on the peripheral blood smear and elevated reticulocyte count.
actual_diagnosis: 16. Sickle cell anemia, ICD-10 code D57.9

doctor_vignette: A 21-year-old male presents with short stature and delayed puberty. Physical exam reveals a height of 5'2", webbed neck, and broad chest. Labs show elevated FSH and LH levels, and karyotyping confirms a 45,X karyotype. The patient expresses concern about infertility and his appearance.

A 15-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of persistent facial pain and pressure, particularly around the cheeks and forehead, accompanied by nasal congestion and purulent nasal discharge for the past week. On physical examination, tenderness is noted over the maxillary and frontal sinuses, and there is erythema in the nasal mucosa. A CT scan of the sinuses reveals opacification of the maxillary sinuses, consistent with acute sinusitis.

A 47-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of increasing hand and foot size over the past few years. On physical exam, notable findings include enlarged extremities, facial changes such as prominent jaw and enlarged nasal features, and thickened skin. Laboratory tests reveal elevated insulin-like growth factor 1 (IGF-1) levels and MRI shows a pituitary adenoma.

An 108-year-old male presents with unintentional weight loss and increased fatigue over the past month. On physical examination, he exhibits tremors, a rapid heart rate of 110 bpm, and a warm, moist skin texture. Thyroid function tests reveal elevated free T4 and suppressed TSH levels, confirming hyperthyroidism.

A 124-year-old male presents with persistent joint pain and stiffness, primarily in his hands and knees. Physical examination reveals swelling and tenderness in multiple joints, along with a decreased range of motion. Laboratory tests show elevated rheumatoid factor and anti-CCP antibodies, with an ESR of 45 mm/hr indicating inflammation.

A 141-year-old female presents with increased shortness of breath and a persistent cough producing yellow sputum. Physical examination reveals wheezing, decreased breath sounds bilaterally, and use of accessory muscles for breathing. A chest X-ray shows hyperinflation of the lungs with an increased anterior-posterior diameter, and pulmonary function tests indicate a significant reduction in FEV1/FVC ratio, confirming airflow obstruction.
actual_diagnosis: 5. Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, ICD-10 code J44.9

doctor_vignette: A 51-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of itchy, red patches on his forearms and behind his knees that have persisted for several weeks. On physical examination, there are scaly, erythematous lesions with excoriations indicative of scratching. No specific lab tests are needed as the clinical presentation is classic for eczema, although a patch test was negative for allergens.

A 60-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of palpitations and shortness of breath that started suddenly two hours ago. Physical examination reveals an irregularly irregular pulse at a rate of 120 beats per minute, along with mild jugular venous distension. An ECG shows atrial fibrillation with no evidence of acute ischemia, and a chest X-ray is unremarkable.

A 53-year-old male presents with chronic diarrhea, abdominal bloating, and unintentional weight loss over the past six months. Physical examination reveals a distended abdomen and signs of malnutrition including dry skin and muscle wasting. Serological tests show elevated tissue transglutaminase antibodies (tTG-IgA) and a low hemoglobin level indicating anemia. An endoscopy with biopsy reveals villous atrophy in the small intestine.

A 91-year-old female presents with recurrent episodes of palpitations, severe headaches, and sweating. On physical examination, her blood pressure is noted to be 180/100 mmHg with a heart rate of 110 bpm. Laboratory tests reveal elevated serum catecholamines and a CT scan shows a 4 cm adrenal mass consistent with pheochromocytoma.

A 148-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of a painful, blistering rash on her right torso. Physical examination reveals grouped vesicular lesions in a dermatomal distribution, accompanied by erythema and tenderness. The patient also reports prodromal symptoms of fever and malaise one week prior. Laboratory tests show a positive PCR for varicella-zoster virus from the vesicular fluid.

A 69-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of persistent low back pain that has worsened over the past month. On physical examination, she demonstrates decreased spinal mobility and tenderness in the lumbar region. A dual-energy X-ray absorptiometry (DEXA) scan reveals a T-score of -2.8, indicating significant bone loss. Her medical history includes menopause at age 50 and a sedentary lifestyle.

A 21-year-old female presents to the emergency department with complaints of severe fatigue and decreased urine output over the past week. On physical examination, she has mild edema in her lower extremities and her blood pressure is elevated at 150/90 mmHg. Laboratory results reveal a serum creatinine level of 3.2 mg/dL, indicating acute kidney injury, with a BUN of 40 mg/dL and urinalysis showing proteinuria and hematuria.
actual_diagnosis: 14. Acute kidney injury, ICD-10 code N17.9

doctor_vignette: A 103-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of recurrent, debilitating headaches occurring 15 days per month for the past year. On physical examination, she demonstrates tenderness in the temporal area and reports associated symptoms of nausea and photophobia during her episodes. Neurological examination reveals no focal deficits, and an MRI of the brain shows no acute lesions but confirms chronic changes consistent with age.

A 49-year-old female presents with excessive daytime sleepiness and episodes of sudden muscle weakness triggered by laughter. During the physical exam, she exhibits signs of cataplexy, with no neurological deficits noted. Polysomnography reveals a short sleep latency and multiple sleep-onset REM periods, confirming the diagnosis.

A 37-year-old female presents with persistent cough and recurrent lung infections. On physical examination, she exhibits digital clubbing and wheezing upon auscultation. Chest X-ray reveals hyperinflation and bronchiectasis, while sweat chloride testing shows elevated chloride levels, confirming the diagnosis.

A 2-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of persistent fever and a rash that has developed over the past week. On physical examination, the child exhibits a butterfly-shaped erythematous rash on the cheeks and is noted to have joint swelling in the knees. Laboratory tests reveal a positive antinuclear antibody (ANA) test and elevated levels of anti-double-stranded DNA antibodies, along with mild anemia.
actual_diagnosis: 16. Systemic lupus erythematosus, ICD-10 code M32.9

doctor_vignette: A 149-year-old male presents with recurrent episodes of joint swelling and pain, particularly in the knees and elbows. Physical examination reveals significant hemarthrosis in both knees and mild bruising on the forearms. Laboratory tests show aPTT prolonged at 45 seconds with normal PT and platelet count, and factor VIII activity is markedly reduced at 3%.

An 82-year-old male presents with acute chest pain and shortness of breath. On physical examination, he has pallor and jaundice, with a heart rate of 110 bpm and decreased breath sounds on the left side. A complete blood count reveals hemoglobin of 6.5 g/dL with a high reticulocyte count, and a chest X-ray shows signs of acute chest syndrome. The patient has a known history of sickle cell disease.
actual_diagnosis: 17. Sickle cell disease, ICD-10 code D57.9

doctor_vignette: A 43-year-old female presents to the emergency department with fever, chills, and severe abdominal pain. On examination, she is tachycardic, hypotensive, and has a distended abdomen with rebound tenderness. Laboratory tests reveal leukocytosis, elevated lactate levels, and blood cultures are positive for E. coli. A CT scan shows perforation of the bowel with associated free air.

A 137-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of persistent heartburn and regurgitation after meals. Physical examination reveals mild epigastric tenderness but no rebound tenderness or guarding. An esophagogastroduodenoscopy (EGD) shows evidence of erosive esophagitis and a hiatal hernia. The patient reports frequent nocturnal symptoms and has been using over-the-counter antacids with minimal relief.
actual_diagnosis: Acid reflux disease, ICD-10 code K21.9

doctor_vignette: A 147-year-old male presents with progressive unilateral hearing loss and occasional tinnitus in the right ear over the past six months. Upon examination, he exhibits diminished auditory acuity and a positive Romberg test, indicating balance issues. MRI of the brain reveals a well-defined mass in the right cerebellopontine angle consistent with an acoustic neuroma.

An 84-year-old female presents with persistent nightmares and severe anxiety following a car accident six months ago. On physical exam, she appears withdrawn and exhibits signs of hypervigilance, such as an exaggerated startle response. No critical lab or imaging findings are noted; however, she reports significant distress and avoidance behaviors related to reminders of the trauma.
actual_diagnosis: Post-traumatic stress disorder, ICD-10 code F43.10

doctor_vignette: A 79-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of persistent abdominal pain and bloody diarrhea for the past two weeks. Physical examination reveals tenderness in the left lower quadrant and a palpable abdominal mass. Laboratory tests show elevated inflammatory markers (CRP and ESR) and a colonoscopy reveals mucosal ulceration consistent with ulcerative colitis.

A 97-year-old female presents with complaints of increasing abdominal swelling and fatigue over the past month. Physical examination reveals ascites, jaundice, and spider angiomas. Laboratory tests show elevated liver enzymes (AST and ALT), low albumin, and a prolonged prothrombin time, while an abdominal ultrasound confirms hepatomegaly and portal hypertension.
actual_diagnosis: Cirrhosis of the liver, ICD-10 code K74.60

doctor_vignette: A 40-year-old male presents with progressive muscle weakness and difficulty climbing stairs.
