On physical examination, he exhibits muscle wasting, particularly in the proximal muscles, and demonstrates a positive Gowers' sign. Serum creatine kinase levels are significantly elevated, and genetic testing reveals a deletion in the dystrophin gene.
actual_diagnosis: Duchenne muscular dystrophy, ICD-10 code G71.0

doctor_vignette: A 104-year-old female presents with recurrent abdominal pain and bloating for the past six months, accompanied by alternating diarrhea and constipation. Physical examination reveals a soft abdomen with tenderness in the lower quadrants but no rebound tenderness or guarding. Laboratory tests show normal complete blood count and metabolic panel, with no signs of infection or inflammation. Colorectal imaging is unremarkable, ruling out structural abnormalities.
actual_diagnosis: Irritable bowel syndrome, ICD-10 code K58.9

doctor_vignette: A 28-year-old female presents with progressive chorea and cognitive decline over the past year. On physical examination, she demonstrates involuntary movements of her limbs and facial grimacing, along with mild psychiatric symptoms of depression. Genetic testing reveals the presence of the CAG repeat expansion in the HTT gene, confirming the diagnosis.

A 92-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of a progressively enlarging neck mass over the past few months. On physical examination, a firm, non-tender nodule is palpated in the right lobe of the thyroid, and there is mild cervical lymphadenopathy. Ultrasound reveals a 3 cm hypoechoic lesion with microcalcifications in the thyroid gland, and fine needle aspiration biopsy confirms malignancy.

A 126-year-old male presents with persistent heartburn and regurgitation after meals. Physical examination reveals mild epigastric tenderness and no signs of abdominal distension. An upper gastrointestinal endoscopy shows esophagitis consistent with acid reflux, and a pH probe confirms abnormal esophageal acid exposure.
actual_diagnosis: Esophageal reflux disease, ICD-10 code K21.9

doctor_vignette: A 90-year-old female presents with progressive dyspnea on exertion over the past six months and a persistent dry cough. Physical examination reveals fine crackles on auscultation bilaterally and clubbing of the fingers. High-resolution CT scan shows reticular opacities and honeycombing in the lower lobes, while pulmonary function tests indicate restrictive lung disease with decreased DLCO.
actual_diagnosis: Idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis, ICD-10 code J84.112

doctor_vignette: A 55-year-old female presents with persistent fatigue and pruritus for the past six months. On physical examination, she has xanthomas on her eyelids and dry skin. Laboratory tests reveal elevated alkaline phosphatase levels (450 U/L) and positive antimitochondrial antibodies (AMA). Abdominal ultrasound shows normal biliary tree with no obstruction.
actual_diagnosis: Primary biliary cholangitis, ICD-10 code K74.3

doctor_vignette: A 96-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of worsening shortness of breath and productive cough for the past three days. Physical examination reveals crackles on lung auscultation, decreased breath sounds in the right lower lobe, and a temperature of 101°F. Chest X-ray shows right lower lobe consolidation, and sputum culture is positive for Klebsiella pneumoniae.
actual_diagnosis: Pneumonia due to Klebsiella pneumoniae, ICD-10 code J18.0

doctor_vignette: A 77-year-old female presents with complaints of persistent headaches and dizziness for the past month. On physical examination, her blood pressure is found to be 160/95 mmHg, and she has mild bilateral retinal changes noted during fundoscopic examination. Laboratory tests show normal electrolytes and kidney function, with no significant findings on chest X-ray.

A 134-year-old male presents with fatigue and decreased appetite over the past month. On physical examination, he has pallor, lower extremity edema, and hypertension. Laboratory tests reveal elevated serum creatinine levels of 3.5 mg/dL and a glomerular filtration rate (GFR) of 25 mL/min, indicating significant renal impairment.
actual_diagnosis: 7. Chronic renal failure, ICD-10 code N18.9

doctor_vignette: A 65-year-old female presents with complaints of bilateral knee pain that worsens with activity and improves with rest. On physical examination, there is tenderness and crepitus in both knees, along with decreased range of motion. X-rays show joint space narrowing and osteophyte formation consistent with osteoarthritis.

A 17-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of itchy, red patches on his elbows and knees that have persisted for several weeks. Physical examination reveals well-defined erythematous plaques covered with silvery scales on extensor surfaces and scalp. No significant laboratory abnormalities are noted, but a skin biopsy shows hyperkeratosis and acanthosis, consistent with psoriasis.

A 105-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of persistent facial pain and pressure, worsening over the past week. Physical examination reveals tenderness over the maxillary sinuses and purulent nasal discharge. A CT scan of the sinuses shows mucosal thickening and fluid levels in the maxillary sinuses, indicating infection. Her vital signs are stable, but she exhibits mild fever and fatigue.

A 126-year-old female presents to the emergency department with acute chest pain radiating to her left arm and shortness of breath. On examination, she exhibits diaphoresis, tachycardia, and an irregular heartbeat. ECG shows ST-segment elevation in the inferior leads, and cardiac troponin levels are significantly elevated. Her medical history includes hypertension and diabetes.
actual_diagnosis: 6. Acute myocardial infarction, ICD-10 code I21.9

doctor_vignette: A 35-year-old male presents with polyuria, polydipsia, and unexplained weight loss over the past month. Upon examination, he has dry mucous membranes and significant fatigue. Laboratory tests reveal a fasting blood glucose level of 250 mg/dL and an HbA1c of 10.5%. Ketones are present in the urine, indicating possible diabetic ketoacidosis.
actual_diagnosis: 4. Diabetes mellitus type 1, ICD-10 code E10.9

doctor_vignette: A 127-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of wheezing and shortness of breath that has worsened over the past week. On physical examination, she exhibits prolonged expiratory phase and decreased breath sounds bilaterally. A peak flow meter reading shows a significant decline from her baseline, and a chest X-ray reveals hyperinflation of the lungs. Laboratory tests indicate elevated eosinophil levels, suggesting an allergic component to her respiratory symptoms.

A 126-year-old male presents with complaints of unintentional weight loss of 10 pounds over the past month, increased heart rate, and anxiety. On physical examination, he exhibits fine tremors in his hands, a prominent goiter, and warm, moist skin. Laboratory tests reveal elevated serum T4 levels and suppressed TSH, confirming hyperthyroidism.

A 116-year-old male presents with chronic diarrhea, weight loss, and abdominal distension. Physical exam reveals a thin, frail appearance with signs of malnutrition, and abdominal tenderness upon palpation. Laboratory tests show elevated anti-tissue transglutaminase IgA antibodies and low hemoglobin levels indicating anemia.

A 115-year-old female presents with fatigue and joint pain, particularly in her hands and knees. On physical examination, she exhibits a butterfly-shaped rash across her cheeks and nose, as well as bilateral swelling of the wrists. Laboratory tests reveal a positive antinuclear antibody (ANA) test and elevated anti-double-stranded DNA antibodies, indicating an autoimmune process.
actual_diagnosis: 14. Systemic lupus erythematosus, ICD-10 code M32.9

doctor_vignette: A 32-year-old female presents with auditory hallucinations and delusions of persecution, expressing fears that she is being watched. Physical examination reveals disorganized speech and a flat affect. Cognitive testing indicates impaired insight and judgment. No significant abnormalities are found on routine blood tests or brain imaging.

A 78-year-old male presents with severe pain and swelling in his right big toe, which started suddenly last night. On examination, the toe is erythematous, warm, and exquisitely tender to touch. Laboratory tests reveal elevated serum uric acid levels of 8.5 mg/dL and joint aspiration shows needle-shaped crystals under polarized light microscopy.

A 19-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of persistent cough and shortness of breath, especially during physical activity. Physical examination reveals prolonged expiration, wheezing, and diminished breath sounds bilaterally. A chest X-ray shows hyperinflation of the lungs, and spirometry confirms a reduced FEV1/FVC ratio, indicative of airflow obstruction.
actual_diagnosis: 17. Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), ICD-10 code J44.9

doctor_vignette: A 17-year-old female presents with sudden onset of right-sided facial weakness and inability to close her right eye. On physical examination, there is noticeable drooping of the right side of her face, with an inability to smile or raise her eyebrow on that side. Neurological examination reveals no other deficits, and a CT scan of the brain shows no evidence of stroke or mass effect. There are no significant findings in her laboratory tests, including complete blood count and metabolic panel.

A 106-year-old female presents with recurrent joint dislocations and skin that is unusually elastic and fragile. Physical examination reveals hypermobile joints and extensive scarring on her forearms from minor injuries. Genetic testing shows a COL5A1 mutation consistent with Ehlers-Danlos syndrome.

A 72-year-old female presents with fatigue and pallor. On physical examination, she exhibits conjunctival pallor and a heart rate of 102 bpm. Laboratory results reveal a hemoglobin level of 9.2 g/dL and serum ferritin of 10 ng/mL, indicating iron deficiency anemia.
actual_diagnosis: 18. Anemia due to iron deficiency, ICD-10 code D50.9

doctor_vignette: A 13-year-old female presents with sudden onset of lower extremity weakness and numbness, along with urinary incontinence over the past two days. Physical examination reveals loss of deep tendon reflexes and sensory loss below the T10 level. MRI of the spinal cord shows inflammation at the thoracic region, with no evidence of compression or structural lesions. Laboratory tests reveal elevated IgG index, suggesting intrathecal synthesis of antibodies.

A 94-year-old male presents with fatigue and recent unintentional weight loss. On physical examination, he has xanthomas on his elbows and a blood pressure of 150/90 mmHg. Laboratory results reveal a total cholesterol level of 320 mg/dL and LDL cholesterol of 200 mg/dL, indicating significantly elevated lipid levels.

A 59-year-old female presents with severe abdominal pain radiating to her back, along with nausea and vomiting. Physical examination reveals tenderness in the epigastric region and guarding. Laboratory tests show elevated serum amylase and lipase levels, and an abdominal ultrasound reveals peritoneal fluid and an enlarged pancreas.

A 132-year-old male presents with complaints of increased hand and foot size over the past few years, along with noticeable facial changes such as a protruding jaw and enlarged nose. Physical examination reveals coarse facial features, thickened skin, and enlarged extremities. Laboratory tests show elevated insulin-like growth factor 1 (IGF-1) levels, and an MRI of the pituitary gland demonstrates a pituitary adenoma.

A 46-year-old male presents with widespread musculoskeletal pain and fatigue lasting over six months. Physical examination reveals tenderness in multiple trigger points, along with generalized stiffness. No significant lab abnormalities are noted, including negative rheumatoid factor and normal inflammatory markers. Imaging studies are unremarkable, ruling out other conditions.

An 81-year-old female presents with worsening joint pain and swelling in her hands and knees over the past month. On examination, she has dactylitis in her right middle finger and erythematous plaques on her elbows. X-rays reveal joint space narrowing and periarticular bone changes consistent with inflammatory arthritis. Laboratory results show elevated ESR and CRP levels, along with a positive family history of psoriasis.

A 4-year-old male presents with persistent abdominal pain and fatigue. On physical examination, he has a noticeable bronze skin discoloration and hepatomegaly. Laboratory results reveal elevated serum ferritin levels and transferrin saturation of 90%.

A 2-year-old female presents with developmental delays and jaundice. On physical examination, she displays hepatomegaly and has a characteristic Kayser-Fleischer ring noted during ophthalmologic evaluation. Laboratory tests reveal elevated serum copper levels and low serum ceruloplasmin, confirming the suspicion of Wilson’s disease.

A 44-year-old female presents with a 5-day history of high fever, conjunctivitis, and a rash. On examination, she has cracked lips, cervical lymphadenopathy, and swelling of the hands and feet. Laboratory tests reveal elevated inflammatory markers, including C-reactive protein and erythrocyte sedimentation rate, and echocardiogram shows mild coronary artery dilation.

A 39-year-old male presents with excessive fatigue, weight gain, and increased body hair. Physical examination reveals hypertension and signs of secondary sexual characteristic changes such as gynecomastia. Laboratory tests show elevated 17-hydroxyprogesterone levels and low cortisol, indicating adrenal insufficiency.
actual_diagnosis: Congenital adrenal hyperplasia, ICD-10 code E25.0

doctor_vignette: A 99-year-old female presents with severe muscle pain and weakness after a fall at home. On physical examination, she exhibits significant tenderness in her lower extremities and decreased range of motion. Laboratory tests reveal elevated serum creatine kinase levels (CK) of 15,000 U/L and myoglobinuria. Her urine dipstick shows a positive result for blood, indicating the presence of myoglobin.

A 44-year-old female presents with complaints of increasing shortness of breath and palpitations. On examination, she is noted to have a tall stature, arachnodactyly, and a loud systolic murmur indicative of aortic regurgitation. An echocardiogram reveals dilation of the aortic root, consistent with Marfan syndrome.

A 70-year-old male presents with progressive dysphagia for solids and liquids over the past six months, accompanied by regurgitation of undigested food and weight loss of 15 pounds. Upon physical examination, he appears malnourished, and auscultation reveals decreased bowel sounds. A barium swallow study shows a dilated esophagus with incomplete lower esophageal sphincter relaxation, consistent with achalasia.

A 134-year-old male presents with increasing pain and discomfort in his right arm. On physical examination, multiple café-au-lait spots and neurofibromas are noted on his skin, particularly on the trunk and extremities. A recent MRI of the brain shows no tumors, but the presence of plexiform neurofibromas is confirmed in the cervical region. Genetic testing reveals a mutation in the NF1 gene.

A 135-year-old male presents with episodic headaches, palpitations, and severe hypertension. On examination, his blood pressure is consistently elevated at 210/110 mmHg, and he exhibits signs of pallor and diaphoresis. Laboratory tests reveal elevated serum catecholamines and a CT scan shows a hypervascular adrenal mass consistent with pheochromocytoma.

A 1-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of lethargy and decreased appetite. On physical examination, he is noted to have pallor and mild splenomegaly. Laboratory results reveal a hemoglobin level of 8.5 g/dL with normal reticulocyte count and elevated inflammatory markers. Further evaluation shows a chronic infection contributing to his anemia.
actual_diagnosis: Anemia due to chronic disease, ICD-10 code D63.9

doctor_vignette: A 25-year-old male presents to the emergency department with a chief complaint of severe headache, fever, and neck stiffness. On physical examination, he exhibits photophobia and a positive Brudzinski's sign. Lumbar puncture reveals cloudy cerebrospinal fluid with a high white blood cell count and elevated protein levels, consistent with bacterial meningitis. Blood cultures confirm the presence of Streptococcus pneumoniae.

A 93-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of persistent headaches for the past week. On physical examination, his blood pressure is recorded at 180/95 mmHg, and he exhibits mild left ventricular hypertrophy on an echocardiogram. No acute distress is noted, but he has a history of non-compliance with antihypertensive medications.

A 96-year-old female presents with social withdrawal and difficulty in communication, expressing frustration over her inability to connect with family members. Physical examination reveals a lack of eye contact and repetitive hand movements. No significant abnormalities were found in routine laboratory tests or imaging, suggesting no underlying neurological disorders.

A 121-year-old male presents with worsening shortness of breath and fatigue over the past month. Physical examination reveals elevated blood pressure at 190/100 mmHg, a third heart sound (S3), and bilateral lower extremity edema. An echocardiogram shows left ventricular hypertrophy and reduced ejection fraction, confirming the diagnosis.
actual_diagnosis: Hypertensive heart disease, ICD-10 code I11.9

doctor_vignette: A 39-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of severe mood swings, characterized by episodes of heightened energy and irritability followed by deep depressive phases. Physical exam reveals rapid speech and increased motor activity during manic episodes, along with a flat affect during depressive phases. No significant abnormalities were found in routine lab tests, and a mood chart shows alternating periods of mania and depression over the past year.

A 107-year-old male presents with worsening shortness of breath and persistent edema in his lower extremities. Physical examination reveals bilateral crackles upon auscultation and pitting edema up to the knees. A chest X-ray shows cardiomegaly and pulmonary congestion, while BNP levels are significantly elevated at 900 pg/mL.
actual_diagnosis: 8. Congestive heart failure, ICD-10 code I50.9

doctor_vignette: A 3-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of persistent knee pain and difficulty in walking. Physical examination reveals swelling and tenderness over the right knee, with limited range of motion and crepitus noted during flexion and extension. An X-ray shows joint space narrowing and subchondral sclerosis, indicating degenerative changes consistent with early-onset osteoarthritis.

A 144-year-old female presents with increased thirst and frequent urination over the past month. Physical examination reveals a BMI of 32, dry mucous membranes, and a glucose level of 220 mg/dL. Laboratory tests show an elevated HbA1c of 8.5%, indicating poor glycemic control.
actual_diagnosis: 5. Type 2 diabetes mellitus, ICD-10 code E11.9

doctor_vignette: A 53-year-old male presents with persistent fatigue, joint pain in the hands and knees, and a rash on his face that worsens with sun exposure. Physical examination reveals a malar rash and bilateral swelling of the joints. Laboratory tests show positive antinuclear antibodies (ANA) and elevated anti-double-stranded DNA antibodies. His complement levels are low, indicating ongoing inflammation.
actual_diagnosis: 11. Systemic lupus erythematosus, ICD-10 code M32.9

doctor_vignette: A 22-year-old male presents with fatigue and a family history of heart disease. Physical examination reveals a BMI of 28 and xanthomas on his elbows. Laboratory results indicate a total cholesterol level of 280 mg/dL and triglycerides at 200 mg/dL, confirming dyslipidemia.

A 51-year-old male presents to the emergency department with complaints of decreased urine output and fatigue over the past week. On physical examination, he is found to have elevated blood pressure, mild edema in the lower extremities, and dry mucous membranes. Laboratory tests reveal a serum creatinine level of 4.2 mg/dL and a blood urea nitrogen (BUN) of 30 mg/dL, indicating acute renal failure.
actual_diagnosis: 13. Acute renal failure, ICD-10 code N17.9

doctor_vignette: A 22-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of sudden onset pain and swelling in her right big toe, which began overnight. On physical exam, the affected joint is erythematous, warm, and tender to palpation. Laboratory tests reveal elevated serum uric acid levels of 8.5 mg/dL, and a joint aspiration shows needle-shaped monosodium urate crystals under polarized light microscopy.

An 81-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of itchy, red patches on her elbows and scalp that have persisted for several weeks. Upon examination, there are well-demarcated, erythematous plaques covered with silvery scales on her extensor surfaces and scalp. No significant laboratory abnormalities are noted, and a skin biopsy confirms the diagnosis of psoriasis.

A 3-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of unusual behaviors, including talking to imaginary friends and displaying disorganized play. During the physical exam, she shows signs of social withdrawal and has difficulty engaging with her caregiver. No significant findings were noted on laboratory tests or imaging, which were performed to rule out other conditions.

A 149-year-old male presents with persistent wheezing and shortness of breath, particularly at night. On examination, he exhibits prolonged expiratory phase and bilateral wheezing on auscultation. Peak expiratory flow rate is measured at 50% of his predicted value, indicating significant obstruction. Chest X-ray shows hyperinflation, consistent with asthma exacerbation.

A 46-year-old female presents with fatigue and weakness for the past month. On physical examination, she is pale and has a heart rate of 102 beats per minute. Laboratory tests reveal a hemoglobin level of 10.2 g/dL and a mean corpuscular volume (MCV) of 78 fL, indicating microcytic anemia. No sources of bleeding are identified on further evaluation.

A 135-year-old female presents with severe fatigue and episodes of joint pain. On examination, she exhibits pallor and jaundice, with notable swelling in her hands and feet. Laboratory results reveal a hemoglobin level of 7.5 g/dL with the presence of sickle-shaped red blood cells on a peripheral blood smear.
actual_diagnosis: 20. Sickle cell disease, ICD-10 code D57.9

doctor_vignette: A 96-year-old male presents with persistent dry mouth and dry eyes, reporting difficulty swallowing and a gritty sensation in his eyes. Physical examination reveals swollen parotid glands and conjunctival injection. Laboratory tests show positive anti-SSA/Ro antibodies and reduced salivary flow on sialography.

A 119-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of widespread musculoskeletal pain and fatigue lasting for several months. Physical examination reveals tenderness in multiple trigger points and a decrease in range of motion, but no signs of inflammation or joint swelling. Routine lab tests show normal results, and imaging studies are unremarkable, ruling out other conditions.

A 19-year-old female presents with persistent right arm pain and numbness, especially after prolonged periods of studying or using her laptop. Physical examination reveals a positive Adson's test and diminished radial pulse on the affected side. MRI of the neck shows an anatomical variant with mild compression of the brachial plexus. Electromyography indicates signs of nerve compression consistent with thoracic outlet syndrome.
actual_diagnosis: 23. Thoracic outlet syndrome, ICD-10 code G54.0

doctor_vignette: A 129-year-old female presents with joint pain and frequent bruising. On examination, her skin is hyperelastic and she has hypermobile joints, particularly in her fingers and knees. Notably, she has experienced multiple joint dislocations over the past year. Genetic testing reveals a mutation consistent with Ehlers-Danlos syndrome.

A 65-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of increasing shortness of breath and a chronic cough that has worsened over the past few months. On physical examination, she exhibits wheezing, decreased breath sounds bilaterally, and clubbing of the fingers. A chest X-ray reveals hyperinflation of the lungs, and spirometry shows a FEV1/FVC ratio of 0.55, indicating obstructive lung disease.
actual_diagnosis: Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), ICD-10 code J44.9

doctor_vignette: An 110-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of recurrent, unilateral headaches that have intensified over the past week. On physical examination, she exhibits mild photophobia and tenderness in the temporal region, but no neurological deficits are noted. Vital signs are stable, and a CT scan of the head shows no acute intracranial abnormalities, ruling out other causes of headache.
actual_diagnosis: Migraine without aura, ICD-10 code G43.909

doctor_vignette: A 133-year-old female presents with persistent heartburn and regurgitation, particularly after meals. On physical examination, she exhibits epigastric tenderness but no signs of acute distress. An upper gastrointestinal endoscopy reveals esophageal inflammation and no structural abnormalities. A pH probe test confirms a low esophageal pH, consistent with acid reflux disease.
actual_diagnosis: Acid reflux disease (Gastroesophageal reflux disease), ICD-10 code K21.9

doctor_vignette: An 82-year-old female presents with persistent feelings of unease and excessive worry about her health and family. On physical examination, she exhibits mild tremors and a notable increase in heart rate, but no other significant findings. Laboratory tests, including a complete blood count and thyroid function tests, return within normal ranges. No imaging studies were performed as there were no indications of acute pathology.

An 88-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of persistent itchy rashes on her arms and legs. Physical examination reveals dry, erythematous patches with excoriations and lichenification. No significant lab results are indicated, as the condition is diagnosed clinically without the need for imaging.

A 95-year-old male presents with fatigue and a rash on his face, which he describes as a butterfly-shaped erythematous lesion. Physical examination reveals mucosal ulcers and joint swelling in his hands. Laboratory tests show a positive antinuclear antibody (ANA) test and low complement levels, suggesting an autoimmune process.

A 130-year-old male presents with increasing forgetfulness and confusion over the past year. Physical examination reveals disorientation to time and place, with mild aphasia and impaired judgment. Neuroimaging shows significant cortical atrophy consistent with neurodegenerative changes. Routine laboratory tests are unremarkable, ruling out metabolic causes of cognitive decline.

A 10-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of persistent cough and difficulty breathing for the past three days. Physical exam reveals decreased breath sounds on the right side, dullness to percussion, and a fever of 102°F. Chest X-ray shows right lower lobe consolidation consistent with pneumonia. A complete blood count indicates leukocytosis with a left shift.

A 9-year-old female presents with persistent neck pain and stiffness, especially after prolonged periods of reading or using electronic devices. Physical examination reveals reduced range of motion in the cervical spine and tenderness along the cervical paravertebral muscles. X-rays show mild degenerative changes in the cervical vertebrae, consistent with early spondylosis.

A 120-year-old female presents with complaints of irregular menstrual cycles and hirsutism. On physical examination, she has a body mass index (BMI) of 32 and exhibits acanthosis nigricans. Laboratory tests reveal elevated androgen levels and an ultrasound shows multiple cysts on the ovaries. These findings are consistent with her diagnosis.
actual_diagnosis: Polycystic ovary syndrome, ICD-10 code E28.2

doctor_vignette: A 111-year-old male presents with abdominal swelling and persistent abdominal pain. On physical examination, a palpable mass is noted in the lower abdomen, and the patient exhibits signs of ascites. Imaging studies reveal an enlarged left adnexal mass consistent with ovarian pathology. CA-125 levels are significantly elevated, suggesting malignancy.

A 35-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of persistent fatigue lasting over six months, which worsens after minimal exertion. Physical examination reveals mild lymphadenopathy and no signs of infection or other systemic illness. Laboratory tests, including complete blood count and thyroid function, return normal, with no abnormalities detected on imaging studies.
actual_diagnosis: Chronic fatigue syndrome, ICD-10 code G93.3

doctor_vignette: A 122-year-old male presents with fatigue and decreased appetite over the past month. Physical examination reveals mild edema in the lower extremities and a blood pressure of 150/90 mmHg. Laboratory tests show a serum creatinine level of 1.8 mg/dL and an estimated glomerular filtration rate (eGFR) of 45 mL/min, indicating stage 3 chronic kidney disease.
actual_diagnosis: Chronic kidney disease, stage 3, ICD-10 code N18.3

doctor_vignette: A 76-year-old male presents with severe pain and swelling in his right lower leg, with overlying erythema and a fever of 101.5°F. Physical exam reveals necrotic tissue at the site with a foul odor and crepitus. MRI shows extensive soft tissue edema and fascial involvement, confirming the suspicion of necrotizing fasciitis.

A 104-year-old female presents with fatigue and jaundice. On physical examination, she exhibits scleral icterus and mild abdominal tenderness in the right upper quadrant. Laboratory tests reveal elevated liver enzymes (ALT 300 U/L, AST 250 U/L) and positive Hepatitis C antibody. A subsequent HCV RNA test confirms active infection.

A 115-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of palpitations and shortness of breath. On physical examination, her heart rate is found to be 130 beats per minute, and she exhibits slight jugular venous distension. An ECG reveals sinus tachycardia, and basic metabolic panel shows mild hypokalemia.

A 38-year-old male presents to the clinic with complaints of persistent headaches and occasional dizziness. On physical examination, his blood pressure is measured at 150/95 mmHg, and he is found to have mild bilateral retinal changes. Routine laboratory tests reveal elevated serum creatinine levels, indicating possible renal involvement.

A 93-year-old female presents with increased thirst and frequent urination over the past month. Physical examination reveals a BMI of 32, and her skin shows signs of dryness. Laboratory results indicate a fasting blood glucose level of 180 mg/dL and HbA1c of 8.2%.
actual_diagnosis: 2. Type 2 diabetes mellitus, ICD-10 code E11.9

doctor_vignette: A 36-year-old female presents to the emergency department with a chief complaint of severe headache, fever, and confusion. On physical examination, she exhibits signs of meningeal irritation, including a positive Brudzinski's sign, and she appears disoriented. A CT scan of the head shows unilateral temporal lobe edema, and lumbar puncture reveals elevated white blood cell count with a predominance of lymphocytes and positive PCR for Herpes Simplex Virus.
actual_diagnosis: Herpes simplex encephalitis, ICD-10 code B00.3

doctor_vignette: A 140-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of worsening shortness of breath and wheezing, especially during exertion. Upon physical examination, she displays a prolonged expiratory phase and bilateral wheezing on auscultation. Peak expiratory flow rate testing shows a significant reduction of 60% from her baseline, indicating obstructive airway disease. Chest X-ray reveals hyperinflation but no acute abnormalities.

A 110-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of bilateral knee pain, worsening over the past year. Physical examination reveals crepitus and tenderness in both knees, with a range of motion limited to 90 degrees. X-rays show joint space narrowing and osteophyte formation consistent with osteoarthritis.

A 57-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of persistent sadness and loss of interest in activities he once enjoyed. On physical exam, he exhibits psychomotor retardation, flat affect, and difficulty concentrating during the assessment. Laboratory tests reveal normal thyroid function and a complete blood count, ruling out other causes of his symptoms.
actual_diagnosis: 6. Major depressive disorder, ICD-10 code F33.1

doctor_vignette: A 54-year-old female presents with severe abdominal pain radiating to the back, associated with nausea and vomiting. On physical examination, she exhibits rebound tenderness and guarding in the upper abdomen. Laboratory tests reveal elevated serum amylase and lipase levels, and an abdominal ultrasound shows peritoneal fluid and an enlarged pancreas. These findings are consistent with acute pancreatitis.

A 60-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of itchy, red patches on his elbows and knees that have persisted for several months. Physical examination reveals well-defined, erythematous plaques covered with silvery scales on extensor surfaces. No laboratory tests are necessary for diagnosis, but a skin biopsy confirms the presence of psoriatic lesions.

A 101-year-old female presents with fatigue and generalized weakness. Physical examination reveals pallor, a heart rate of 110 bpm, and a systolic murmur. Laboratory tests show a hemoglobin level of 8 g/dL and low serum ferritin levels, indicating iron deficiency.
actual_diagnosis: 11. Anemia due to iron deficiency, ICD-10 code D50.9

doctor_vignette: A 45-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of recurrent episodes of loss of consciousness and muscle jerking lasting about 1-2 minutes over the past month. Physical examination reveals no focal neurological deficits, and she appears well-nourished and in no acute distress. An EEG shows generalized spike-and-wave discharges consistent with generalized epilepsy, and MRI of the brain is unremarkable.

A 7-year-old male presents with chronic diarrhea and abdominal distension for the past three months. On physical examination, he is noted to have weight loss and a distended abdomen with tenderness in the epigastric region. Laboratory tests reveal elevated tissue transglutaminase IgA antibodies and a decreased hemoglobin level, indicating possible malabsorption.

A 68-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of persistent heartburn and regurgitation after meals. On physical examination, he demonstrates mild epigastric tenderness but has no signs of acute distress. An upper endoscopy reveals erosive esophagitis consistent with gastroesophageal reflux disease. A pH study confirms abnormal esophageal acid exposure.
actual_diagnosis: 14. Gastroesophageal reflux disease, ICD-10 code K21.9

doctor_vignette: A 111-year-old female presents with widespread joint pain and fatigue over the past month. Physical examination reveals a malar rash across her cheeks, and she has bilateral swelling in the wrists and knees. Laboratory tests show a positive antinuclear antibody (ANA) test and elevated erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR), indicating inflammation.
actual_diagnosis: 13. Systemic lupus erythematosus, ICD-10 code M32.9

doctor_vignette: A 20-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of unintentional weight loss and increased heart rate over the past month. Physical examination reveals exophthalmos, a fine tremor in her hands, and a rapid heart rate of 120 beats per minute. Laboratory tests show elevated free T4 and suppressed TSH levels, confirming hyperthyroidism.

A 117-year-old female presents with auditory hallucinations and paranoid delusions, claiming that her caregivers are plotting against her. Physical examination reveals disorganized speech and a flat affect. No significant findings are noted in her routine lab work or imaging studies, ruling out other organic causes. The patient's history reveals episodes of confusion and social withdrawal over the past few months.

A 7-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of decreased urine output for the past two days. Physical examination reveals mild edema and elevated blood pressure. Laboratory results show a serum creatinine level of 2.5 mg/dL and a blood urea nitrogen (BUN) of 40 mg/dL, indicating acute kidney injury.
actual_diagnosis: 17. Acute kidney injury, ICD-10 code N17.9

doctor_vignette: A 141-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of persistent numbness and tingling in her right hand, particularly affecting the thumb, index, and middle fingers. On physical examination, Tinel's sign and Phalen's maneuver are positive. Nerve conduction studies reveal delayed median nerve conduction at the wrist, consistent with carpal tunnel syndrome.
actual_diagnosis: 18. Carpal tunnel syndrome, ICD-10 code G56.00

doctor_vignette: A 131-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of a rapidly enlarging, asymmetrical mole on his back that has changed in color over the past month. Physical examination reveals a 2 cm irregularly shaped lesion with a dark brown to black hue and irregular borders. Lymphadenopathy is noted in the left axilla. A biopsy confirms the diagnosis of malignant melanoma.
actual_diagnosis: 20. Malignant melanoma of skin, ICD-10 code C43.9

doctor_vignette: A 60-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of persistent joint pain and stiffness, particularly in the hands and knees, that worsens in the morning. Physical examination reveals swelling and tenderness in multiple joints, with a notable ulnar deviation of the fingers. Laboratory tests show positive rheumatoid factor and elevated anti-CCP antibodies, along with increased ESR and CRP levels.

A 79-year-old male presents to the emergency department with difficulty breathing and swelling of the face and throat after eating shrimp. Physical examination reveals wheezing, urticaria, and hypotension. Initial lab results show elevated serum tryptase levels and a significant drop in oxygen saturation. The patient reports no prior history of shellfish allergies.

A 91-year-old female presents with progressive shortness of breath and fatigue over the past month. On physical examination, she exhibits bilateral lower extremity edema and a third heart sound (S3) on auscultation. An echocardiogram reveals left ventricular dilation and reduced ejection fraction of 35%. Serum BNP levels are significantly elevated at 800 pg/ml, indicating heart failure.

A 135-year-old male presents with complaints of excessive daytime sleepiness and loud snoring, reported by his caregiver. Physical examination reveals obesity, a thick neck, and hypertension. Overnight polysomnography shows recurrent apneas and hypopneas with significant oxygen desaturation. No other significant lab abnormalities are noted.

A 110-year-old female presents with sudden onset of right-sided facial droop and inability to close her right eye. On physical examination, there is notable asymmetry in her facial movements, with weakness in the right upper and lower face, while the forehead is affected. No significant findings are noted on CT imaging of the head, and laboratory tests reveal no signs of infection or other underlying pathology.

A 114-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of recurrent severe headaches occurring every few weeks, often accompanied by nausea and sensitivity to light. Physical examination reveals a mildly elevated blood pressure but is otherwise unremarkable with no neurological deficits. A CT scan of the head shows no acute intracranial abnormalities, ruling out other causes of headache.

A 132-year-old male presents with recurrent episodes of involuntary jerking movements and loss of consciousness that have been occurring for the past six months. On physical examination, he exhibits postictal confusion and muscle soreness, but no focal neurological deficits are noted. EEG findings reveal generalized spike-and-wave discharges, consistent with seizure activity. MRI of the brain shows no structural abnormalities.

An 87-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of worsening shortness of breath and a productive cough for the past three days. On physical examination, he exhibits decreased breath sounds and crackles in the right lower lung field. Chest X-ray reveals right lower lobe consolidation, and laboratory tests show elevated white blood cell count with a left shift, indicating infection.
actual_diagnosis: Pneumonia due to unspecified organism, ICD-10 code J18.9

doctor_vignette: A 91-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of right lower abdominal pain that began 24 hours ago, accompanied by nausea and decreased appetite. Physical examination reveals tenderness in the right lower quadrant with rebound tenderness and guarding. Laboratory tests show elevated white blood cell count (WBC 15,000/uL) and a CT scan confirms an enlarged, inflamed appendix.

A 124-year-old female presents with acute onset of fever, palpitations, and confusion. On examination, she is tachycardic with a heart rate of 150 bpm, and exhibits tremors and a prominent goiter. Laboratory tests reveal a significantly elevated free T4 level and suppressed TSH, confirming hyperthyroidism. Chest X-ray shows signs of heart failure, consistent with thyroid storm.

A 92-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of rectal bleeding and discomfort during bowel movements. Physical examination reveals external hemorrhoids, which are swollen and tender, as well as mild anemia on lab results with a hemoglobin level of 10.2 g/dL. No imaging is necessary as the clinical findings are consistent with the diagnosis.

A 23-year-old female presents to the emergency department with a chief complaint of palpitations and shortness of breath for the past hour. On physical examination, her heart rate is 130 beats per minute, blood pressure is 110/70 mmHg, and she appears anxious. An ECG shows sinus tachycardia with no ischemic changes, and basic metabolic panel reveals normal electrolyte levels.

A 117-year-old male presents with a complaint of bilateral breast tenderness and palpable lumps in the breast tissue. Physical examination reveals multiple, mobile, and tender cystic masses in both breasts, with no overlying skin changes. A mammogram shows dense breast tissue with multiple cysts, consistent with fibrocystic changes. No significant abnormalities are noted in laboratory tests.
actual_diagnosis: Fibrocystic breast disease, ICD-10 code N60.1

doctor_vignette: A 65-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of recurrent hives for the past three months, accompanied by intense itching. Physical examination reveals multiple raised, erythematous wheals on his trunk and extremities, with no signs of angioedema. Laboratory tests, including a complete blood count and thyroid function tests, return normal, ruling out other underlying conditions.

A 26-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of persistent facial pressure and nasal congestion for the past three months. Physical examination reveals tenderness over the maxillary sinuses and postnasal drip. A CT scan of the sinuses shows mucosal thickening in the maxillary and ethmoid sinuses, consistent with chronic sinusitis.

A 58-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of persistent fever lasting for over five days. Physical examination reveals conjunctival injection, erythematous rash, cervical lymphadenopathy, and cracking of the lips. Laboratory tests show an elevated erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR) and thrombocytosis, while echocardiography indicates mild coronary artery dilation.

A 4-year-old male presents with progressive difficulty in using his right hand for daily activities and a noticeable decline in coordination. Physical examination reveals rigidity and bradykinesia on the right side, along with a marked asymmetry in reflexes. MRI of the brain shows atrophy of the right parietal lobe and basal ganglia, supporting the suspicion of corticobasal degeneration.

A 65-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of itchy, purplish papules on her wrists and ankles that have persisted for several weeks. Physical examination reveals multiple flat-topped, polygonal lesions with a lace-like pattern on the oral mucosa. There are no signs of infection, and a biopsy of the skin confirms a diagnosis of lichenoid tissue change without malignancy.

A 107-year-old male presents with severe epigastric pain and nausea for the past week. Physical examination reveals tenderness in the epigastric region and signs of anemia, including pallor. A gastroscopy shows a bleeding gastric ulcer, and lab tests indicate low hemoglobin levels and elevated urea, suggesting significant gastrointestinal bleeding.

A 15-year-old female presents with fatigue, unexplained weight loss, and recurrent infections over the past month. Physical exam reveals splenomegaly and pallor. Complete blood count shows elevated white blood cell count with a high percentage of immature granulocytes and a positive Philadelphia chromosome test.
actual_diagnosis: Chronic myeloid leukemia, ICD-10 code C92.1

doctor_vignette: A 62-year-old male presents with fatigue and pallor. On physical examination, he has mild splenomegaly and a noticeable pallor of the conjunctiva. Complete blood count reveals microcytic anemia with hemoglobin levels at 9 g/dL and elevated levels of fetal hemoglobin. Iron studies show normal iron levels, suggesting a non-iron deficiency anemia.

A 147-year-old female presents with a non-healing ulcerated lesion on her right cheek that has persisted for several months. Physical examination reveals a pearly, raised border with telangiectasia surrounding the ulceration. A biopsy confirms the diagnosis of basal cell carcinoma, and no lymphadenopathy is noted on examination. Imaging shows no signs of metastasis, confirming localized disease.
actual_diagnosis: Basal cell carcinoma, ICD-10 code C44.91

doctor_vignette: A 129-year-old male presents with increasing fatigue and weakness over the past month. On physical examination, he is pale, with a heart rate of 110 bpm and a blood pressure of 100/60 mmHg. Laboratory tests reveal a hemoglobin level of 8.5 g/dL and a mean corpuscular volume (MCV) of 78 fL, indicating microcytic anemia. No obvious source of bleeding is noted on further investigation.

A 51-year-old female presents with a persistent cough lasting over three weeks, accompanied by night sweats and weight loss. Physical examination reveals decreased breath sounds in the right lung and dullness to percussion. A chest X-ray shows right upper lobe consolidation, and sputum analysis reveals acid-fast bacilli.

A 141-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of worsening cough and shortness of breath over the past week. Physical examination reveals decreased breath sounds and crackles in the right lower lung field, along with a fever of 101°F. Chest X-ray shows right lower lobe opacity consistent with pneumonia, and blood tests indicate elevated white blood cell count.
actual_diagnosis: Pneumonia, unspecified organism, ICD-10 code J18.9

doctor_vignette: A 5-year-old male presents with growth failure and delayed puberty. On physical examination, he exhibits short stature for his age, decreased muscle mass, and diminished body hair. Laboratory tests reveal low levels of growth hormone, ACTH, and LH, consistent with pituitary dysfunction.

A 41-year-old male presents to the emergency department with chest pain radiating to his left arm and shortness of breath that started 30 minutes ago. On physical examination, he is diaphoretic, with a blood pressure of 150/90 mmHg and a heart rate of 110 bpm. An ECG shows ST-segment elevation in the anterior leads, and cardiac troponin I levels are markedly elevated.

A 41-year-old male presents with fatigue and decreased urine output over the past month. Physical examination reveals mild edema in the lower extremities and hypertension (BP 150/95 mmHg). Laboratory tests show an elevated serum creatinine level of 2.5 mg/dL and a glomerular filtration rate (GFR) of 30 mL/min, indicating impaired kidney function.
actual_diagnosis: 9. Chronic kidney disease, ICD-10 code N18.9

doctor_vignette: A 38-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of persistent shortness of breath and wheezing, particularly at night. On physical examination, she exhibits prolonged expiratory phase and diffuse wheezing bilaterally. Peak expiratory flow rate measured in the office is 60% of her predicted value, indicating significant airflow obstruction. Chest X-ray shows no acute abnormalities, supporting the diagnosis of asthma exacerbation.

A 139-year-old male presents with chronic diarrhea and significant weight loss over the past three months. Physical examination reveals abdominal distension and signs of malnutrition, including muscle wasting. Laboratory tests show elevated tissue transglutaminase antibodies and a low hemoglobin level, indicating anemia. A small bowel biopsy confirms villous atrophy consistent with celiac disease.

A 56-year-old female presents to the emergency department with chief complaint of difficulty breathing and hives after eating shrimp. On physical exam, she exhibits wheezing, facial swelling, and generalized urticaria. Vital signs show hypotension with a blood pressure of 80/50 mmHg. Laboratory results reveal elevated serum tryptase levels consistent with an anaphylactic reaction.
actual_diagnosis: Anaphylaxis due to food, ICD-10 code T78.2

doctor_vignette: A 39-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of unintentional weight loss and increased heart rate over the past month. On physical exam, she demonstrates hyperhidrosis, a fine tremor in her hands, and exophthalmos. Laboratory results reveal a suppressed TSH level and elevated free T4, confirming hyperthyroidism.

An 89-year-old male presents to the emergency department with palpitations and shortness of breath that started abruptly. On physical examination, his heart rate is irregularly irregular at 130 beats per minute, and he has mild bilateral lower extremity edema. An ECG reveals atrial fibrillation with no evident acute ischemic changes, and his electrolytes show slight hypokalemia.

A 133-year-old female presents with increasing memory loss and confusion over the past year. Physical examination reveals disorientation to time and place, along with difficulty following simple commands. Brain MRI shows global atrophy typical of neurodegenerative conditions, and cognitive testing demonstrates significant impairment in memory recall and executive function.

A 64-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of persistent joint pain and swelling in her hands and knees for the past three months. On physical examination, there is notable bilateral synovitis and morning stiffness lasting over an hour. Laboratory tests reveal positive rheumatoid factor and elevated anti-CCP antibodies, along with increased ESR and CRP levels indicating inflammation.

A 29-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of persistent itchy rashes on her arms and neck for the past month. On physical examination, there are erythematous, scaly patches with lichenification noted in the flexural areas. A patch test reveals no allergens, and skin scraping is negative for fungal elements.

A 14-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of persistent cough and shortness of breath, especially during physical activity. On physical examination, he exhibits wheezing and decreased breath sounds bilaterally. A chest X-ray shows hyperinflation of the lungs, and pulmonary function tests indicate reduced FEV1/FVC ratio consistent with obstructive lung disease. The patient has a history of significant exposure to secondhand smoke.
actual_diagnosis: 19. Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, ICD-10 code J44.9

doctor_vignette: A 50-year-old male presents with severe pain and swelling in his right big toe, which began suddenly overnight. On physical examination, the affected joint is erythematous and warm to touch, with limited range of motion due to pain. Serum uric acid levels are markedly elevated at 9.5 mg/dL, confirming the diagnosis.

A 111-year-old male presents with fatigue and joint pain, particularly in the hands and knees. On physical examination, he shows a butterfly rash across his cheeks and erythematous lesions on his forearms. Laboratory tests reveal a positive antinuclear antibody (ANA) test and elevated double-stranded DNA antibodies, indicating an autoimmune process.
actual_diagnosis: 20. Systemic lupus erythematosus, ICD-10 code M32.9

doctor_vignette: A 7-year-old male presents with persistent fatigue, weight loss, and recurrent abdominal pain. On physical examination, he has hyperpigmentation of the skin, particularly in the creases and mucous membranes, along with low blood pressure. Laboratory tests reveal hyponatremia, hyperkalemia, and elevated ACTH levels, indicative of adrenal insufficiency.

A 49-year-old male presents with chronic widespread pain and fatigue lasting over six months. Physical exam reveals tenderness in multiple trigger points, particularly in the neck, shoulders, and lower back. No significant abnormalities are noted in routine lab tests, including complete blood count and inflammatory markers, which are within normal limits. Imaging studies, including X-rays, show no evidence of joint degeneration or other musculoskeletal abnormalities.

A 17-year-old female presents with persistent fatigue and unexplained weight loss over the past month. Physical examination reveals lymphadenopathy in the cervical and axillary regions, and splenomegaly is noted. A complete blood count shows elevated lymphocyte levels and a chest CT scan indicates enlarged mediastinal lymph nodes.

A 128-year-old female presents with recurrent back pain and a recent history of a hip fracture after a minor fall. On physical examination, she exhibits kyphosis and reduced spinal mobility. A DEXA scan reveals a T-score of -3.5, indicating severe osteoporosis. Laboratory tests show normal calcium and vitamin D levels.

A 128-year-old female presents with worsening shortness of breath and fatigue over the past month. On examination, she has elevated blood pressure of 180/95 mmHg, a third heart sound (S3), and bilateral lower extremity edema. An echocardiogram reveals left ventricular hypertrophy and diastolic dysfunction, and her BNP level is significantly elevated at 500 pg/mL.
actual_diagnosis: 23. Hypertensive heart disease, ICD-10 code I11.9

doctor_vignette: A 147-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of social withdrawal and difficulty communicating with family members. On physical examination, he demonstrates stereotypical hand movements and limited eye contact. Neurodevelopmental assessments reveal persistent deficits in social communication and interaction, with no significant abnormalities in MRI imaging. Laboratory tests show normal metabolic function, supporting the diagnosis of Autism spectrum disorder.
actual_diagnosis: Autism spectrum disorder, ICD-10 code F84.0

doctor_vignette: A 65-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of severe headache and neck stiffness for the past two days. On physical examination, he exhibits photophobia and a positive Brudzinski's sign. Lumbar puncture reveals cloudy cerebrospinal fluid with a white blood cell count of 800 cells/mm³, predominantly neutrophils, and positive cultures for Streptococcus pneumoniae.

A 138-year-old female presents with persistent fatigue and unexplained weight loss over the past three months. Physical examination reveals significant cervical lymphadenopathy and splenomegaly. A chest X-ray shows mediastinal lymphadenopathy, and a biopsy of the lymph node confirms Reed-Sternberg cells. Blood work shows elevated LDH levels and anemia.

A 106-year-old female presents with persistent fatigue and swelling in her lower extremities. Physical examination reveals a heart rate of 110 bpm, and the patient exhibits bilateral leg edema. A serologic test confirms the presence of Trypanosoma cruzi antibodies, indicating Chagas disease.

A 114-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of worsening knee pain, particularly during ambulation. Physical examination reveals crepitus and tenderness over the medial compartment of both knees, with limited range of motion. X-rays show joint space narrowing and osteophyte formation consistent with osteoarthritis.

A 102-year-old female presents with severe daytime fatigue and frequent episodes of waking at night. Physical examination reveals obesity and a prominent neck circumference of 16 inches. Pulse oximetry shows intermittent oxygen desaturation during sleep, with a recorded apnea-hypopnea index of 32 events per hour on overnight polysomnography. The patient reports loud snoring and gasping for air, especially noted by her caregivers.

A 26-year-old female presents to the emergency department with a chief complaint of fever and chills for the past three days. On physical examination, she is tachycardic with a heart rate of 120 bpm, hypotensive with a blood pressure of 88/54 mmHg, and has warm, flushed skin. Laboratory results show a white blood cell count of 18,000 cells/mm³, elevated lactate levels at 4.5 mmol/L, and a positive blood culture for Escherichia coli.

A 10-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of progressive muscle weakness and a rash on her eyelids and knuckles. Physical examination reveals heliotrope rash, Gottron's papules, and muscle tenderness. Laboratory tests show elevated creatine kinase levels and positive anti-Jo-1 antibodies, confirming muscle inflammation.

An 18-year-old male presents to the emergency department with a chief complaint of decreased urination and fatigue over the past three days. Physical examination reveals dry mucous membranes and a blood pressure of 90/60 mmHg. Laboratory tests show elevated serum creatinine levels of 4.2 mg/dL and a blood urea nitrogen (BUN) of 48 mg/dL, indicating acute renal failure. Urinalysis reveals concentrated urine with a specific gravity of 1.030 and few renal tubular epithelial cells.
actual_diagnosis: Acute renal failure, ICD-10 code N17.9

doctor_vignette: A 16-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of persistent cough and fever for three days. Physical examination reveals tachypnea, decreased breath sounds on the right side, and dullness to percussion. Chest X-ray shows a right lower lobe infiltrate consistent with pneumonia. Complete blood count indicates leukocytosis with a left shift.

A 122-year-old male presents with severe agitation, palpitations, and fever. On examination, he is tachycardic at 150 bpm, has a temperature of 39.5°C, and displays tremors and altered mental status. Laboratory tests reveal elevated free T4 levels and suppressed TSH, confirming hyperthyroidism.

A 36-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of persistent itchy rashes on her arms and neck that have worsened over the past month. On physical examination, there are erythematous patches with scaling and excoriation, particularly in flexural areas. No significant lab results were noted; a skin biopsy ruled out other dermatitis types, supporting the diagnosis.

A 64-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of a painful rash on the right side of his chest that started two days ago. On physical exam, there are clustered vesicular lesions on an erythematous base in a dermatomal distribution, accompanied by tenderness to palpation. A Tzanck smear reveals multinucleated giant cells, supporting the diagnosis.

A 143-year-old male presents to the emergency department with a chief complaint of fever and confusion. On physical examination, he is noted to have tachycardia, hypotension, and a temperature of 102°F. Laboratory results reveal elevated white blood cell count, elevated lactate levels, and signs of acute kidney injury. No specific organism is identified in blood cultures.
actual_diagnosis: Sepsis, unspecified organism, ICD-10 code A41.9

doctor_vignette: A 20-year-old female presents with persistent bone pain in her pelvis and lower back. On physical examination, there is tenderness over the hip and enlargement of the femur. X-rays reveal an abnormal thickening of the pelvic bones and cortical bone expansion. Serum alkaline phosphatase levels are significantly elevated, indicating increased bone turnover.
actual_diagnosis: Paget's disease of bone, ICD-10 code M88.9

doctor_vignette: A 121-year-old female presents with complaints of extreme fatigue and weight gain over the past few months. On physical examination, she shows dry skin, bradycardia, and swelling of the face and extremities. Laboratory tests reveal an elevated TSH level and low free T4, indicating hypothyroidism.

A 126-year-old male presents with worsening fatigue and bone pain, particularly in the lumbar region. On physical examination, he exhibits pallor, tenderness over the spine, and noticeable bruising. Laboratory results reveal an elevated serum protein level with a monoclonal spike and a significant decrease in hemoglobin, alongside skeletal X-rays showing lytic lesions in the vertebrae.

A 94-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of increasing discomfort from multiple skin nodules. Physical examination reveals neurofibromas on his trunk and extremities, as well as café-au-lait spots on his back. Imaging studies show no evidence of significant central nervous system involvement, but numerous subcutaneous tumors are noted. His family history is positive for similar skin lesions, suggestive of a genetic predisposition.

A 39-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of recurrent wheezing and shortness of breath, especially at night and after exercise. On physical exam, he exhibits prolonged expiration and diffuse wheezing bilaterally. Spirometry reveals a reduced FEV1/FVC ratio, indicating airflow obstruction that improves with bronchodilator use.

A 93-year-old female presents with persistent knee pain, especially during ambulation. On examination, there is notable crepitus and limited range of motion in both knees, with tenderness on palpation. X-rays reveal joint space narrowing and osteophyte formation consistent with osteoarthritis.

An 8-year-old male presents to the emergency department with severe chest pain radiating to his left arm and shortness of breath. On physical examination, he is diaphoretic, with a heart rate of 120 bpm and blood pressure of 90/60 mmHg. An ECG shows ST-segment elevation in the anterior leads, and cardiac troponin levels are significantly elevated. These findings suggest acute myocardial infarction.
actual_diagnosis: 8. Acute myocardial infarction, ICD-10 code I21.9

doctor_vignette: A 75-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of severe pain and swelling in her right big toe that started suddenly the night before. On physical exam, the affected joint is erythematous, warm, and exquisitely tender to touch. Laboratory tests reveal elevated serum uric acid levels of 9.2 mg/dL, confirming the diagnosis.

A 144-year-old female presents with fatigue and occasional chest discomfort. Physical examination reveals a body mass index of 32 and xanthomas on her elbows. Laboratory tests show total cholesterol levels of 320 mg/dL and triglycerides of 200 mg/dL, indicating significant dyslipidemia.

A 24-year-old female presents to the emergency department after experiencing a generalized tonic-clonic seizure lasting approximately three minutes. On physical examination, she is postictal, with confusion and muscle soreness noted. A head MRI shows no structural abnormalities, and routine blood tests including electrolytes and glucose are within normal limits. The patient reports a history of similar episodes occurring intermittently over the past year.

A 41-year-old male presents with complaints of increasing shortness of breath and fatigue over the past month. On physical exam, he has bilateral lower extremity edema and an elevated jugular venous pressure. A chest X-ray shows cardiomegaly, and a BNP level is markedly elevated at 600 pg/mL, indicating heart failure.

A 123-year-old male presents with fatigue and weakness over the past month. On physical exam, he is pale and exhibits tachycardia. Laboratory results show a hemoglobin level of 9.0 g/dL and low serum ferritin levels. There are no signs of acute bleeding or chronic disease.
actual_diagnosis: 18. Iron deficiency anemia, ICD-10 code D50.9

doctor_vignette: An 85-year-old female presents with fatigue and joint pain in her hands and knees. On physical examination, she has a malar rash and tenderness in multiple joints. Laboratory tests reveal positive antinuclear antibodies (ANA) and low complement levels. A urinalysis shows proteinuria, suggesting potential kidney involvement.
actual_diagnosis: 19. Systemic lupus erythematosus, ICD-10 code M32.9

doctor_vignette: A 110-year-old male presents with persistent abdominal pain and diarrhea for several weeks. Physical examination reveals tenderness in the right lower quadrant and signs of weight loss. Laboratory tests show elevated C-reactive protein (CRP) and anemia, while a CT scan reveals segmental thickening of the ileum consistent with inflammatory bowel disease.

An 85-year-old female presents with gradual vision loss and difficulty seeing in low light. Upon examination, her intraocular pressure is measured at 28 mmHg, and a visual field test reveals significant peripheral vision loss. Fundoscopic examination shows cupping of the optic nerve head, consistent with glaucoma. She has no significant past ocular history and denies any acute eye pain.

A 62-year-old male presents with severe fatigue and persistent swelling in his legs. On physical examination, he has a blood pressure of 180/100 mmHg, bilateral pitting edema in the lower extremities, and a notable decrease in urine output. Laboratory results reveal a serum creatinine level of 8.5 mg/dL and an estimated GFR of 10 mL/min, indicating significant renal impairment.
actual_diagnosis: 21. End-stage renal disease, ICD-10 code N18.6

doctor_vignette: A 48-year-old female presents with sudden onset right-sided facial weakness and drooping of the right corner of the mouth, which began this morning. On physical examination, she exhibits inability to close her right eye and a loss of nasolabial fold on that side. Neurological examination reveals normal strength in extremities and intact sensation. A CT scan of the head shows no evidence of acute intracranial pathology, supporting the diagnosis of Bell's palsy.

A 100-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of severe back pain after a fall at home. On physical examination, he exhibits kyphosis and tenderness over the thoracic spine. A lateral spine X-ray reveals vertebral compression fractures at T12 and L1. Laboratory tests show normal calcium levels but elevated alkaline phosphatase, indicating potential bone turnover.

An 118-year-old female presents with fatigue and unexplained weight gain over the past few months. On physical examination, she exhibits dry skin, bradycardia, and a notable goiter. Laboratory tests reveal elevated TSH levels of 12.5 mIU/L and low free T4 levels of 0.7 ng/dL, indicating an underactive thyroid.

An 108-year-old female presents with persistent fatigue and joint pain in her hands and knees. Physical examination reveals a malar rash across her cheeks and nose, along with swollen joints. Laboratory tests show elevated anti-nuclear antibodies (ANA) and low complement levels, consistent with systemic lupus erythematosus.
actual_diagnosis: Lupus erythematosus, systemic, ICD-10 code M32.9

doctor_vignette: A 114-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of persistent heartburn and regurgitation that has worsened over the past month. Physical examination reveals tenderness in the epigastric region and a dry cough. An upper gastrointestinal endoscopy shows esophagitis, and a pH monitoring test confirms acid reflux.
actual_diagnosis: Gastroesophageal reflux disease, ICD-10 code K21.9

doctor_vignette: A 98-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of severe headache and altered mental status. On examination, she exhibits nuchal rigidity, photophobia, and confusion. Lumbar puncture reveals cloudy cerebrospinal fluid with a high white blood cell count, predominantly neutrophils, and positive gram stain for Streptococcus pneumoniae. Blood cultures are also positive for the same organism.

A 134-year-old female presents with severe right upper quadrant abdominal pain and fever. On examination, she demonstrates rebound tenderness and guarding in the right upper quadrant. Ultrasound reveals gallbladder wall thickening and the presence of gallstones. Laboratory tests show elevated white blood cell count and liver function tests within normal limits.

An 11-year-old male presents with recurrent abdominal pain and significant discomfort during bowel movements. Physical examination reveals tenderness in the lower abdomen and a palpable mass in the pelvic area. An ultrasound shows the presence of endometrial-like tissue outside the uterus, consistent with endometriosis.

A 113-year-old female presents with persistent pain and swelling in her right knee for the past month. On physical examination, there is notable tenderness, swelling, and limited range of motion in the affected joint, with a palpable mass. X-rays reveal an aggressive bone lesion with a sunburst pattern and soft tissue extension, raising suspicion for malignancy. MRI confirms the presence of a high-grade osteosarcoma originating from the distal femur.

A 144-year-old male presents with acute confusion and a fever of 102°F. Physical examination reveals hypotension (BP 80/50 mmHg), tachycardia (heart rate 120 bpm), and cold, clammy skin. Laboratory results show elevated white blood cell count (21,000/mm³), positive blood cultures for gram-negative bacteria, and metabolic acidosis with a lactate level of 4.5 mmol/L.

A 32-year-old male presents with increasing memory loss and difficulty concentrating over the past year. Neurological examination reveals mild disorientation to time and place, as well as impaired short-term memory. Brain MRI shows nonspecific atrophy but no acute findings. Routine laboratory tests, including thyroid function and vitamin B12 levels, are within normal limits.

A 5-year-old female presents with confusion and difficulty walking, having been recently diagnosed with a severe gastrointestinal disorder leading to malnutrition. On exam, she demonstrates nystagmus and ataxia. Blood tests reveal low thiamine levels and MRI shows symmetric lesions in the thalamus and hypothalamus. The family reports a poor dietary intake due to her illness.

A 141-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of persistent joint pain and difficulty walking. Physical examination reveals short stature, disproportionately short limbs, and a prominent forehead. X-rays show characteristic features of achondroplasia, including shortened long bones and a normal-sized trunk. No metabolic abnormalities are detected in her routine lab work.

A 115-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of uncomfortable sensations in her legs, making it difficult for her to relax and sleep at night. Physical examination reveals mild edema in the lower extremities, but neurological examination is otherwise unremarkable. Lab tests show normal complete blood count and metabolic panel, with no signs of anemia or electrolyte imbalances, ruling out secondary causes.
actual_diagnosis: Restless legs syndrome, ICD-10 code G25.81

doctor_vignette: A 14-year-old female presents with complaints of dry eyes and a persistent dry mouth for the past six months. On examination, she has enlarged parotid glands and decreased tear production noted on Schirmer's test. Laboratory results reveal positive anti-Ro (SS-A) antibodies and a low saliva flow rate.

An 84-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of painful vesicular lesions on his lips and around his mouth that started two days ago. Physical examination reveals multiple clustered vesicles on an erythematous base, and he reports fever and malaise. A PCR test of the lesion fluid confirms the presence of Herpes simplex virus.
actual_diagnosis: Herpes simplex virus infection, ICD-10 code B00.9

doctor_vignette: A 43-year-old male presents with persistent fatigue and unexplained weight loss over the past three months. On physical examination, notable findings include enlarged cervical lymph nodes and splenomegaly. A chest CT scan reveals mediastinal lymphadenopathy, and a lymph node biopsy confirms the diagnosis.

A 7-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of ear pain and fever for two days. Physical examination reveals a bulging, erythematous left tympanic membrane and tenderness upon palpation of the ear. There is also a presence of purulent discharge noted in the ear canal. No imaging is required as the clinical presentation is consistent with acute otitis media.
actual_diagnosis: Acute otitis media, ICD-10 code H65.9

doctor_vignette: A 20-year-old female presents to the emergency department with a chief complaint of excessive thirst and frequent urination for the past week. Physical examination reveals dry mucous membranes and a weight loss of 5 kg since her last visit. Laboratory tests show a blood glucose level of 350 mg/dL and the presence of ketones in the urine.
actual_diagnosis: 5. Type 1 diabetes mellitus, ICD-10 code E10.9

doctor_vignette: An 82-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of persistent knee pain, particularly worsening with activity and improving with rest. Physical examination reveals bilateral knee tenderness, crepitus on movement, and limited range of motion. X-rays show joint space narrowing and osteophyte formation in both knees, indicating degenerative changes.

A 107-year-old male presents with increasing confusion and difficulty with daily activities over the past six months. Physical examination reveals cognitive impairment with disorientation to time and place, along with mild hemiparesis on the right side. Neuroimaging shows multiple small infarcts in the white matter consistent with vascular changes. Laboratory tests indicate no significant metabolic derangements.

A 91-year-old male presents with persistent abdominal pain and weight loss over the past three months. On physical examination, he exhibits signs of malnutrition, including muscle wasting and pallor. Laboratory tests reveal elevated tissue transglutaminase antibodies (tTG-IgA) and low hemoglobin levels. Additionally, a small intestine biopsy indicates villous atrophy consistent with celiac disease.

A 142-year-old female presents with unintentional weight loss and palpitations for the past month. On examination, she has a fine tremor, increased sweating, and a rapid heart rate of 110 beats per minute. Laboratory tests reveal elevated free T4 and suppressed TSH levels, indicating hyperthyroidism.

A 21-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of itchy, red patches on her elbows and knees that have persisted for several weeks. Physical examination reveals well-defined, erythematous plaques covered with silvery-white scales, particularly on extensor surfaces. No significant lab findings are noted, but a skin biopsy confirms the diagnosis of psoriasis.

An 85-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of severe headache and confusion lasting two days. On examination, she exhibits nuchal rigidity, photophobia, and altered mental status. Cerebrospinal fluid analysis reveals a high white blood cell count with predominance of neutrophils, low glucose levels, and elevated protein, consistent with bacterial meningitis.

A 102-year-old male presents with sudden onset of decreased urine output and severe fatigue. On physical exam, he is found to be hypotensive with dry mucous membranes and mild edema in the lower extremities. Laboratory tests reveal elevated serum creatinine levels of 3.5 mg/dL and a BUN of 45 mg/dL, indicating acute kidney injury. Urinalysis shows the presence of casts and protein, further supporting the diagnosis.
actual_diagnosis: 12. Acute renal failure, ICD-10 code N17.9

doctor_vignette: A 130-year-old female presents with severe abdominal pain radiating to the back and nausea. Physical examination reveals tenderness in the epigastric region and a low-grade fever. Laboratory tests show elevated serum lipase and amylase levels, while an abdominal ultrasound indicates the presence of gallstones and peritoneal fluid.

A 5-year-old female presents to the emergency department with complaints of palpitations and intermittent dizziness. On physical examination, she is noted to have an irregularly irregular pulse and a heart rate of 180 beats per minute. An ECG reveals atrial fibrillation with rapid ventricular response, and a chest X-ray shows no significant abnormalities. Blood tests indicate mild hypokalemia.

A 121-year-old male presents with fatigue and weakness over the past month. On physical examination, he is pale, with a heart rate of 102 bpm and a blood pressure of 110/70 mmHg. Laboratory results show a hemoglobin level of 9.5 g/dL, elevated C-reactive protein indicating inflammation, and normal iron studies, suggesting anemia due to chronic disease.
actual_diagnosis: 13. Anemia due to chronic disease, ICD-10 code D63.8

doctor_vignette: A 144-year-old male presents with persistent widespread musculoskeletal pain and fatigue for the past six months. Physical examination reveals tenderness in multiple tender points, particularly in the neck, shoulders, and lower back, with no signs of joint swelling. Laboratory tests, including complete blood count and inflammatory markers, are within normal limits, and imaging studies show no abnormalities. His symptoms have significantly impacted his daily activities and quality of life.

A 98-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of uncontrollable shaking in his hands, particularly noticeable while trying to eat. On physical examination, he exhibits a bilateral postural tremor of the hands, which worsens with movement but improves with rest. Neurological examination reveals no other focal deficits, and routine laboratory tests, including thyroid function and metabolic panel, are within normal limits. Imaging studies of the brain show no acute abnormalities, ruling out other causes of tremor.

A 44-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of severe ear pain in the right ear for the past two days, accompanied by a low-grade fever. On physical examination, there is notable erythema and bulging of the tympanic membrane in the right ear, with decreased mobility on pneumatic otoscopy. The patient reports recent upper respiratory symptoms, and a rapid strep test is negative, ruling out streptococcal infection.
actual_diagnosis: Acute otitis media, ICD-10 code H66.90

doctor_vignette: An 87-year-old female presents with blurred vision in her left eye and difficulty reading. On examination, she has cotton wool spots and retinal hemorrhages in both eyes. Fundoscopic examination reveals microaneurysms and exudates. Her recent HbA1c level is 9.2%, indicating poor glycemic control.
