A 75-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of increasing shortness of breath and a productive cough with green sputum over the past month. Physical examination reveals prolonged expiratory phase, wheezing bilaterally, and use of accessory muscles for breathing. A chest X-ray shows hyperinflation of the lungs, and spirometry indicates a FEV1/FVC ratio of 0.55, confirming airflow obstruction.
actual_diagnosis: 8. Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), ICD-10 code J44.9

doctor_vignette: A 35-year-old male presents with worsening fatigue and tremors over the past month. On physical examination, he demonstrates fine tremors of the hands and a Kayser-Fleischer ring in both eyes. Laboratory tests reveal elevated serum copper levels and decreased ceruloplasmin. MRI of the brain shows basal ganglia changes consistent with Wilson's disease.

A 24-year-old female presents with joint hypermobility and frequent joint dislocations, particularly in her shoulders and knees. On physical examination, skin elasticity is noted to be significantly increased, and bruising is easily observed. A family history of similar symptoms is reported, and genetic testing reveals a mutation consistent with Ehlers-Danlos syndrome.

A 113-year-old female presents with fatigue and palpitations. Physical examination reveals a heart rate of 110 bpm and a heart murmur. An electrocardiogram shows signs of arrhythmia, and serological tests confirm the presence of Trypanosoma cruzi antibodies.

A 148-year-old female presents with a high fever lasting five days, conjunctival injection, and a rash on her trunk and extremities. Physical examination reveals cervical lymphadenopathy and cracked lips. Laboratory tests show elevated inflammatory markers, including CRP and ESR, along with a thrombocytosis.

An 18-year-old male presents with shortness of breath on exertion and persistent fatigue for the past month. On examination, he has bilateral lower extremity edema and elevated jugular venous pressure. Chest X-ray reveals cardiomegaly and pulmonary congestion, while lab tests show elevated B-type natriuretic peptide (BNP) levels.
actual_diagnosis: 5. Congestive heart failure, ICD-10 code I50.9

doctor_vignette: A 31-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of increased thirst, frequent urination, and unexplained weight loss over the past month. Physical examination reveals dry mucous membranes and a body mass index of 22. Laboratory tests show a fasting blood glucose level of 250 mg/dL and ketones present in the urine.
actual_diagnosis: 4. Type 1 diabetes mellitus, ICD-10 code E10.9

doctor_vignette: A 91-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of persistent back pain and increased difficulty with mobility over the past few months. On physical examination, he demonstrates significant kyphosis and tenderness over the thoracic spine. A DEXA scan reveals a T-score of -3.5, indicating severe osteoporosis. Additionally, a recent X-ray shows multiple vertebral fractures without acute trauma.

A 142-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of itchy, red patches on her skin that have persisted for several weeks. Physical examination reveals well-defined, erythematous plaques with silvery scale predominantly on her elbows and knees. No significant abnormalities are noted in laboratory tests, and a skin biopsy confirms the diagnosis of psoriasis.

A 48-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of severe pain and swelling in his right big toe that started suddenly overnight. On physical examination, there is notable erythema, warmth, and tenderness over the affected joint. Laboratory tests reveal an elevated serum uric acid level of 9.2 mg/dL and a joint aspiration shows needle-shaped monosodium urate crystals under polarized light microscopy.

A 32-year-old female presents with fatigue and persistent swelling in her ankles. On physical examination, she has elevated blood pressure and bilateral lower extremity edema. Laboratory results reveal a serum creatinine level of 2.1 mg/dL and a glomerular filtration rate (GFR) of 45 mL/min, indicating impaired kidney function.
actual_diagnosis: 11. Chronic kidney disease, ICD-10 code N18.9

doctor_vignette: A 133-year-old female presents with joint swelling and bruising after a minor fall. Physical examination reveals significant hemarthrosis in the right knee and multiple ecchymoses on her extremities. Laboratory tests show a prolonged activated partial thromboplastin time (aPTT) with normal prothrombin time (PT) and low factor VIII levels.

A 148-year-old female presents with worsening shortness of breath and a persistent cough for the past month. On examination, she has decreased breath sounds bilaterally, wheezing, and a prolonged expiration phase. A chest X-ray shows hyperinflation of the lungs, and spirometry reveals an FEV1/FVC ratio of 55%, confirming airflow limitation.
actual_diagnosis: 15. Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), ICD-10 code J44.9

doctor_vignette: A 20-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of unintentional weight loss and increased heart rate over the past month. On physical examination, he exhibits fine tremors, heat intolerance, and a visibly enlarged thyroid gland. Laboratory tests reveal elevated free T4 and suppressed TSH levels, confirming hyperthyroidism.

A 70-year-old female presents with social withdrawal and difficulty in communication. On physical exam, she exhibits repetitive hand movements and has difficulty maintaining eye contact. Neuropsychological testing reveals significant deficits in social cognition and adaptive functioning, consistent with autism spectrum disorder. No critical lab or imaging results are necessary as the diagnosis is primarily clinical based on behavioral observations.
actual_diagnosis: 18. Autism spectrum disorder, ICD-10 code F84.0

doctor_vignette: A 149-year-old male presents to the emergency department with acute shortness of breath and swelling of the face and tongue after consuming a shellfish meal. On examination, he has wheezing, stridor, and hypotension with a blood pressure of 70/40 mmHg. A rapid bedside test shows elevated serum tryptase levels, indicating anaphylaxis. His oxygen saturation is 85% on room air.

A 50-year-old female presents with a 2-day history of severe headache, fever, and neck stiffness. On examination, she exhibits photophobia and a positive Brudzinski's sign. A lumbar puncture reveals cloudy cerebrospinal fluid with a white blood cell count of 1,200 cells/mm³, predominantly neutrophils, and positive Gram stain for bacteria. Blood cultures are also positive for Streptococcus pneumoniae.

A 117-year-old female presents with complaints of gradual enlargement of her hands and feet over the past few years, along with persistent headaches. Physical examination reveals pronounced facial features, including a protruding jaw and enlarged nose, along with thickened skin on her hands. Serum IGF-1 levels are significantly elevated, and an MRI shows a pituitary adenoma consistent with growth hormone excess.

A 125-year-old female presents with sudden onset of petechiae and purpura on her extremities, along with complaints of fatigue and confusion. Physical examination reveals a low-grade fever, splenomegaly, and significant pallor. Laboratory results show a markedly reduced platelet count of 20,000/µL, elevated lactate dehydrogenase (LDH) levels, and a negative Direct Coombs test, indicating hemolytic anemia. These findings are suggestive of thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura.
actual_diagnosis: Thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura, ICD-10 code D68.6

doctor_vignette: A 2-year-old female presents for a routine check-up with her parents who express concern about her increased irritability and poor feeding. Physical examination reveals elevated blood pressure of 110/70 mmHg, which is above the 95th percentile for her age. No signs of end-organ damage are noted, and laboratory tests show normal renal function and electrolytes. A follow-up echocardiogram is planned to assess for potential underlying causes.

An 108-year-old male presents with severe abdominal pain and nausea. Physical examination reveals tenderness in the epigastric region and mild jaundice. Laboratory tests show elevated serum amylase and lipase levels, and abdominal ultrasound indicates pancreatic edema with no evidence of gallstones.

A 72-year-old male presents with persistent difficulties in maintaining focus and organization, often losing track of conversations and appointments. His mental status exam reveals distractibility and impulsive speech. No significant abnormalities are noted on neurological examination, and laboratory tests, including a CBC and metabolic panel, are within normal limits. Imaging studies show no structural abnormalities in the brain.
actual_diagnosis: 12. Attention-deficit hyperactivity disorder, ICD-10 code F90.9

doctor_vignette: A 130-year-old male presents with persistent fatigue and weight gain over the past six months. Physical examination reveals dry skin, bradycardia, and a delayed deep tendon reflex. Laboratory tests show elevated TSH levels and low free T4, confirming the diagnosis.

A 19-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of persistent lower back pain after a minor fall. Physical examination reveals decreased lumbar lordosis and tenderness on palpation of the lumbar spine. A dual-energy X-ray absorptiometry (DEXA) scan shows a T-score of -2.5, indicating significant bone density loss. Laboratory tests reveal normal calcium and vitamin D levels, ruling out secondary causes of osteoporosis.

A 97-year-old male presents with worsening shortness of breath and wheezing that has been persistent for the past week. On examination, he exhibits prolonged expiratory wheezes and diminished breath sounds on auscultation. A peak flow measurement reveals a marked decrease in expiratory flow rate. Chest X-ray shows hyperinflation consistent with asthma, with no signs of infection.

An 118-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of a rapidly enlarging dark lesion on his right forearm. Physical examination reveals a 2.5 cm irregularly shaped, black and brown pigmented lesion with irregular borders and a rough surface. A biopsy shows malignant melanoma, and imaging reveals no regional lymphadenopathy or distant metastasis.
actual_diagnosis: 14. Melanoma of the skin, ICD-10 code C43.9

doctor_vignette: A 99-year-old female presents with fatigue and decreased appetite over the past month. Physical examination reveals bilateral lower extremity edema and decreased urine output. Laboratory tests show elevated serum creatinine levels of 2.5 mg/dL and a glomerular filtration rate (GFR) of 30 mL/min, indicating impaired kidney function.
actual_diagnosis: 17. Chronic kidney disease, ICD-10 code N18.9

doctor_vignette: A 27-year-old female presents with worsening shortness of breath and fatigue over the past month. On physical examination, she has elevated jugular venous pressure, bilateral lower extremity edema, and crackles noted on lung auscultation. A chest X-ray reveals cardiomegaly and pulmonary congestion, while BNP levels are significantly elevated.
actual_diagnosis: 16. Congestive heart failure, ICD-10 code I50.9

doctor_vignette: A 77-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of persistent fatigue and joint pain, particularly in her hands and knees. On physical examination, she exhibits a malar rash across her cheeks, along with tenderness and swelling in multiple joints. Laboratory tests reveal a positive antinuclear antibody (ANA) test and elevated levels of anti-double-stranded DNA antibodies, consistent with autoimmune activity.
actual_diagnosis: 18. Systemic lupus erythematosus, ICD-10 code M32.9

doctor_vignette: A 33-year-old female presents with complaints of blurred vision and halos around lights. On examination, her intraocular pressure is measured at 28 mmHg, and a visual field test shows peripheral vision loss. Fundoscopic examination reveals cupping of the optic disc, indicating possible glaucoma.

A 73-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of widespread musculoskeletal pain and fatigue lasting over six months. On physical examination, she exhibits tenderness in multiple trigger points and has difficulty with range of motion due to pain. Laboratory tests show normal inflammatory markers and no abnormalities in routine blood work, ruling out other conditions.

A 35-year-old male presents to the emergency department with palpitations and shortness of breath that started suddenly while exercising. On physical examination, his heart rate is irregularly irregular at 150 beats per minute, and he has mild dyspnea. An ECG shows atrial fibrillation with no identifiable P waves, and a chest X-ray reveals no acute cardiopulmonary abnormalities.

A 109-year-old male presents with swelling and tenderness in his left leg. On physical exam, the left calf is markedly swollen and warm to the touch, with positive Homan's sign. Doppler ultrasound reveals a thrombus in the left popliteal vein. His medical history includes prolonged immobility following recent hospitalization for pneumonia.
actual_diagnosis: 23. Deep vein thrombosis, ICD-10 code I82.409

doctor_vignette: A 133-year-old female presents to the emergency department with acute difficulty breathing and swelling of the face and throat after ingesting a peanut butter cookie. Physical exam reveals wheezing, facial edema, and hypotension. Laboratory tests show an elevated serum tryptase level and low oxygen saturation. Immediate treatment with epinephrine is initiated.

A 93-year-old female presents with recurrent bruising and prolonged bleeding from a minor laceration on her arm. Physical examination reveals multiple ecchymoses on her extremities and a slight pallor. Laboratory tests show aPTT of 60 seconds (normal 25-35 seconds) with normal PT, and a factor VIII level of 35% (normal 50-150%).

A 66-year-old male presents with severe pain and swelling in his right big toe, which began suddenly two days ago. On physical examination, the affected joint is erythematous, warm, and tender to touch. Serum uric acid levels are significantly elevated at 9.2 mg/dL, confirming hyperuricemia.

A 47-year-old male presents with complaints of numbness and tingling in his right hand, particularly affecting the thumb, index, and middle fingers. On physical examination, a positive Tinel's sign and Phalen's maneuver are noted, indicating median nerve compression. Nerve conduction studies reveal decreased sensory and motor conduction velocities across the wrist.
actual_diagnosis: 27. Carpal tunnel syndrome, ICD-10 code G56.00

doctor_vignette: A 41-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of severe left lower abdominal pain and fever for the past two days. Physical examination reveals tenderness in the left lower quadrant with rebound tenderness and mild distension. A CT scan of the abdomen shows diverticula in the sigmoid colon with surrounding inflammatory changes, consistent with diverticulitis.

A 101-year-old male presents with progressive lower back pain and difficulty walking, particularly after short distances. On physical exam, he exhibits diminished lower extremity reflexes and a positive straight leg raise test. MRI of the lumbar spine reveals significant narrowing of the spinal canal at L4-L5 due to degenerative changes. His history includes osteoarthritis and chronic pain management.

A 133-year-old female presents with complaints of progressive enlargement of her hands and feet over the past several years. On physical examination, notable findings include pronounced facial features, including a protruding jaw and enlarged nasal features, as well as thickened skin on her palms. An MRI of the pituitary gland reveals a sizable adenoma, and serum growth hormone levels are markedly elevated.

A 43-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of persistent abdominal pain and diarrhea lasting for several weeks. Physical examination reveals tenderness in the right lower quadrant and signs of weight loss. Laboratory tests show elevated C-reactive protein (CRP) and anemia, while a colonoscopy reveals skip lesions and deep ulcers in the ileum.

A 73-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of persistent right upper quadrant pain that worsens after meals. On physical examination, she has tenderness in the right upper abdomen and a positive Murphy's sign. An abdominal ultrasound reveals multiple gallstones in the gallbladder, with no signs of acute cholecystitis.

A 32-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of multiple skin lesions and increasing headaches. Physical examination reveals café-au-lait spots on his torso, axillary freckling, and subcutaneous neurofibromas on his arms. MRI of the brain shows the presence of an optic nerve glioma, consistent with neurofibromatosis type 1.

A 150-year-old female presents with complaints of unintentional weight loss and increased heart rate. On physical examination, she exhibits tremors in her hands, a warm and moist skin texture, and bulging eyes. Laboratory results reveal elevated serum thyroxine (T4) levels and suppressed thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH) levels.

A 34-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of persistent cough and shortness of breath for the past week. Physical examination reveals decreased breath sounds in the right lower lung field and crackles on auscultation. A chest X-ray shows right lower lobe consolidation, and a PCR test for SARS-CoV-2 is positive.
actual_diagnosis: Pneumonia due to coronavirus, ICD-10 code J12.81

doctor_vignette: An 108-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of persistent knee pain and stiffness, particularly worsening in the morning. Physical examination reveals crepitus and limited range of motion in both knees, along with tenderness on palpation. X-rays show joint space narrowing and osteophyte formation consistent with osteoarthritis.

A 55-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of severe pain in her right big toe that started suddenly overnight. On physical examination, the toe is red, swollen, and tender to touch, with a limited range of motion. Lab results reveal elevated serum uric acid levels of 8.5 mg/dL, and a joint aspiration shows the presence of monosodium urate crystals.

A 68-year-old male presents with worsening shortness of breath and wheezing over the past week, particularly at night. On physical examination, he exhibits diffuse wheezing and decreased breath sounds bilaterally. A peak flow measurement shows a significant reduction from his baseline, and a chest X-ray reveals no acute pathology. His history includes smoking for 30 years and a previous diagnosis of allergic rhinitis.

A 121-year-old male presents with fatigue and decreased urine output over the past week. Physical examination reveals dry mucous membranes and mild edema in the lower extremities. Laboratory results indicate elevated serum creatinine levels at 3.2 mg/dL and a BUN of 45 mg/dL, with urinalysis showing no signs of obstruction. Ultrasound of the kidneys shows normal size with no hydronephrosis.
actual_diagnosis: 12. Acute kidney injury, ICD-10 code N17.9

doctor_vignette: A 71-year-old female presents to the emergency department with palpitations and shortness of breath that started 2 hours ago. On physical examination, her heart rate is irregularly irregular at 120 beats per minute, and she exhibits mild edema in her lower extremities. An ECG shows atrial fibrillation with a rapid ventricular response, and her electrolytes reveal hypokalemia.

An 81-year-old male presents with increasing memory loss over the past year, frequently forgetting recent conversations and misplacing items. On physical examination, he demonstrates difficulty with short-term recall and appears disoriented to time. Neuroimaging reveals moderate cerebral atrophy with significant hippocampal involvement. Laboratory tests show normal thyroid function and vitamin B12 levels.

A 37-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of persistent itchy rash on her elbows and knees. Physical examination reveals erythematous, scaly patches with excoriations and lichenification. No laboratory tests are necessary as the diagnosis is based on clinical findings, which are consistent with eczema.

A 13-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of persistent skin tightening and swelling on her fingers and face over the past six months. Physical examination reveals sclerodactyly, telangiectasia on her cheeks, and decreased range of motion in her fingers. Laboratory tests show a positive anti-Scl-70 antibody and elevated ESR, indicating systemic involvement.

A 126-year-old male presents with severe anemia and recurrent pain episodes in his chest and joints. Physical examination reveals pallor, splenomegaly, and tenderness in the lower extremities. Laboratory results show a hemoglobin level of 7 g/dL, with a peripheral blood smear indicating sickle-shaped cells and reticulocytosis. Additionally, elevated bilirubin levels suggest hemolysis.
actual_diagnosis: 18. Sickle cell disease, ICD-10 code D57.9

doctor_vignette: A 3-year-old female presents with severe abdominal pain and vomiting. On physical examination, she exhibits tenderness in the epigastric region and rebound tenderness. Laboratory tests reveal elevated serum lipase levels and a CT scan shows peritoneal fluid consistent with pancreatitis. The child has a history of recent high-fat dietary intake.

A 142-year-old male presents with acute left lower quadrant abdominal pain and fever. Physical examination reveals tenderness and guarding in the left lower abdomen, with decreased bowel sounds. A CT scan of the abdomen shows multiple diverticula with associated inflammation, confirming the diagnosis.

A 35-year-old female presents with progressive muscle weakness, particularly in her eyelids and limbs, worsening with activity. Physical examination reveals ptosis and bilateral weakness in the proximal muscles. A repetitive nerve stimulation test shows a significant decremental response, and serum acetylcholine receptor antibodies are elevated.

A 104-year-old male presents with prolonged bleeding from a minor cut on his forearm that has not stopped after several hours. On physical examination, there are multiple ecchymoses on his extremities and a notable pallor. Laboratory tests reveal a significantly decreased Factor VIII level and an elevated activated partial thromboplastin time (aPTT), consistent with hemophilia A.

A 129-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of acute shortness of breath and cough. Physical examination reveals decreased breath sounds and crackles in the right lower lung field. Chest X-ray shows right lower lobe consolidation, and sputum analysis indicates the presence of aspirated material.
actual_diagnosis: Pneumonia due to aspiration, ICD-10 code J69.0

doctor_vignette: A 47-year-old male presents with auditory hallucinations and disorganized speech, expressing paranoid delusions about being watched. Physical examination reveals a flat affect and poor personal hygiene. Neurological examination is unremarkable, and routine lab tests, including a complete blood count and metabolic panel, show no abnormalities. A CT scan of the brain is normal, ruling out organic causes.

A 40-year-old male presents with progressive dyspnea on exertion and a persistent dry cough for the past six months. On physical examination, clubbing of the fingers and crackles are noted upon auscultation of the lungs. High-resolution CT scan reveals reticular opacities and ground-glass opacities consistent with interstitial lung disease. Pulmonary function tests indicate a restrictive pattern with decreased forced vital capacity.

An 11-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of neck pain and swelling for the past week. On physical examination, there is notable tenderness and enlargement of the thyroid gland, accompanied by mild fever and fatigue. Laboratory tests reveal elevated thyroid peroxidase antibodies and a slightly increased TSH level, indicating thyroid inflammation.

A 26-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of widespread itching and raised welts on his arms and torso that appeared suddenly after eating shellfish. Physical examination reveals multiple erythematous wheals varying in size, with no signs of angioedema or respiratory distress. Laboratory tests show elevated eosinophil count and normal skin biopsy results, ruling out other conditions.

A 6-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of persistent cough and difficulty breathing for the past month. On physical examination, he exhibits tachypnea, digital clubbing, and crackles on auscultation. A high-resolution CT scan of the chest reveals ground-glass opacities and reticular patterns consistent with interstitial lung disease.
actual_diagnosis: Interstitial lung disease, ICD-10 code J84.112

doctor_vignette: A 63-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of easy bruising and petechiae on her lower extremities. Physical examination reveals multiple ecchymoses and scattered petechiae, with no signs of splenomegaly. Laboratory tests show a markedly low platelet count of 40,000/mm³, while other blood counts remain normal.
actual_diagnosis: Idiopathic thrombocytopenic purpura, ICD-10 code D69.3

doctor_vignette: A 29-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of worsening headaches and visual disturbances. On physical examination, multiple café-au-lait spots and several palpable neurofibromas are noted on his torso and limbs. MRI of the brain reveals an optic nerve glioma, consistent with his condition.

A 116-year-old female presents with high fever, chills, and severe fatigue over the past week. Physical examination reveals splenomegaly and pallor. Laboratory tests show a positive rapid diagnostic test for Plasmodium species and a hemoglobin level of 8 g/dL, indicating anemia.

A 127-year-old female presents with recurrent episodes of unresponsiveness and jerking movements of her left arm, occurring approximately twice a week. Neurological examination reveals slight weakness on the right side and a postictal state following the episodes. An EEG shows diffuse slow-wave activity suggestive of seizure activity, while MRI of the brain is unremarkable.

A 104-year-old male presents with persistent pain in his right knee, which worsens with activity and improves with rest. On physical examination, there is notable crepitus upon movement, tenderness along the joint line, and a reduced range of motion. X-rays reveal joint space narrowing, osteophyte formation, and subchondral sclerosis consistent with osteoarthritis.
actual_diagnosis: Osteoarthritis of the knee, ICD-10 code M17.9

doctor_vignette: A 125-year-old male presents with fatigue and decreased appetite. Physical examination reveals mild edema in the lower extremities and hypertension with a blood pressure of 150/90 mmHg. Laboratory results show an elevated serum creatinine level of 2.5 mg/dL and a glomerular filtration rate (GFR) of 45 mL/min, indicating stage 3 chronic kidney disease.
actual_diagnosis: Chronic kidney disease, stage 3, ICD-10 code N18.30

doctor_vignette: A 124-year-old female presents with fatigue and jaundice. On physical examination, she has scleral icterus and mild abdominal tenderness. Laboratory tests reveal elevated alanine aminotransferase (ALT) and aspartate aminotransferase (AST) levels, along with a positive hepatitis C antibody test.

A 136-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of severe swelling in her legs and abdomen for the past week. On physical examination, she demonstrates pitting edema in the lower extremities and ascites. Laboratory tests reveal significant proteinuria of 4.5 g/day and hypoalbuminemia with serum albumin levels at 2.1 g/dL. Urinalysis shows the presence of fatty casts.

A 15-year-old female presents with fatigue and abdominal discomfort. Physical examination reveals mild hepatomegaly and tenderness in the right upper quadrant. Liver function tests show elevated alanine aminotransferase (ALT) and aspartate aminotransferase (AST) levels, while an abdominal ultrasound reveals increased echogenicity of the liver consistent with fatty infiltration.
actual_diagnosis: Nonalcoholic fatty liver disease, ICD-10 code K76.0

doctor_vignette: A 77-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of severe headache and confusion for the past two days. On examination, he is febrile with a stiff neck and photophobia, and he exhibits altered mental status. Lumbar puncture reveals cloudy cerebrospinal fluid with elevated white blood cell count and a predominance of neutrophils, indicating a possible bacterial infection.
actual_diagnosis: Bacterial meningitis, unspecified, ICD-10 code G00.9

doctor_vignette: A 40-year-old female presents with persistent numbness and tingling in her right hand, particularly in the thumb, index, and middle fingers. On physical examination, she exhibits positive Phalen's and Tinel's signs. Nerve conduction studies reveal slowed median nerve conduction across the wrist, confirming the diagnosis.
actual_diagnosis: Carpal tunnel syndrome, ICD-10 code G56.01

doctor_vignette: A 30-year-old female presents to the emergency department with acute chest pain radiating to her left arm, accompanied by shortness of breath and diaphoresis. On physical examination, she exhibits tachycardia and a blood pressure of 90/60 mmHg. An ECG shows ST-segment elevation in the anterior leads, and cardiac troponin levels are significantly elevated. These findings are consistent with myocardial infarction.
actual_diagnosis: Acute myocardial infarction, unspecified, ICD-10 code I21.9

doctor_vignette: A 110-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of persistent fever lasting over five days. Physical exam reveals conjunctival injection, a rash on the trunk, and significant cervical lymphadenopathy. Laboratory tests show elevated inflammatory markers (ESR and CRP) and thrombocytosis. Echocardiogram indicates coronary artery dilation.

A 103-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of chronic constipation and abdominal distension. Physical exam reveals a markedly distended abdomen with palpable fecal impaction and a lack of bowel sounds. Abdominal X-ray shows significant colonic dilation and a transition zone indicative of Hirschsprung disease. No other acute findings are noted.

A 127-year-old female presents with recurrent episodes of syncope and palpitations. Upon examination, she demonstrates a characteristic coved-type ST-segment elevation in leads V1 to V3 on her ECG. Her family history is notable for sudden cardiac death in a male relative at a young age. Laboratory tests reveal no significant electrolyte imbalances.

An 84-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of a rash and fever for the past week. Physical examination reveals an erythema migrans rash on her left thigh, along with bilateral knee swelling and tenderness. Laboratory tests show positive serology for Borrelia burgdorferi, confirming Lyme disease.

An 80-year-old male presents with a 2-day history of a barking cough, hoarseness, and difficulty breathing. On examination, he has stridor at rest and appears anxious, with a respiratory rate of 28 breaths per minute. A neck X-ray shows mild subglottic narrowing consistent with croup. No significant lab abnormalities are noted, but oxygen saturation is 92% on room air.

A 139-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of severe headache and neck stiffness. Upon examination, he exhibits fever, photophobia, and a positive Brudzinski's sign. Lumbar puncture reveals elevated white blood cell count with a predominance of neutrophils and low glucose levels, indicating a possible bacterial infection.

A 149-year-old male presents with persistent bone pain and swelling in the left mandible. Physical examination reveals tenderness and a palpable mass in the affected area, along with skin lesions resembling seborrheic keratosis. CT imaging shows lytic bone lesions in the skull and mandible, while biopsy of the skin lesions confirms the presence of Langerhans cells. Laboratory tests indicate elevated levels of serum uric acid and a mild leukocytosis.
actual_diagnosis: Langerhans cell histiocytosis, ICD-10 code D75.81

doctor_vignette: A 9-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of severe pain and swelling in his right big toe. On physical examination, the toe is erythematous, swollen, and exhibits limited range of motion. Laboratory tests reveal elevated serum uric acid levels of 8.5 mg/dL. Joint aspiration shows needle-shaped crystals under polarized light, confirming the diagnosis.

A 59-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of diminished sexual satisfaction and difficulty achieving orgasm. Physical examination reveals decreased pelvic floor muscle tone and signs of vaginal atrophy. Laboratory tests show elevated FSH and LH levels, indicating menopausal changes. There are no signs of urinary tract infection on urinalysis.

A 133-year-old male presents with complaints of hot flashes and mood swings, which he describes as increasingly bothersome over the past few months. Physical examination reveals a lack of secondary sexual characteristics and notable weight gain. Hormonal panel shows elevated follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) levels and decreased testosterone levels, indicative of hormonal changes typically associated with menopause in males. Imaging studies are unremarkable.

A 19-year-old male presents with progressive cognitive decline, difficulty concentrating, and visual hallucinations over the past three months. Physical examination reveals a tremor in the right hand and rigidity in both upper extremities. Neuroimaging shows cortical atrophy and a decrease in dopamine transporter uptake on SPECT scan, consistent with Lewy body pathology.
actual_diagnosis: Dementia with Lewy bodies, ICD-10 code G31.83

doctor_vignette: A 79-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of excessive hand washing and persistent thoughts that she may have contaminated surfaces in her home. Physical examination reveals no significant abnormalities, but she appears anxious and exhibits repetitive behaviors. No critical lab or imaging results are necessary for diagnosis, as her symptoms are consistent with obsessive-compulsive disorder.

A 117-year-old female presents with a chief complaint of increasing shortness of breath and a persistent cough for the past month. Physical examination reveals prolonged expiratory phase, wheezing, and use of accessory muscles for respiration. Chest X-ray shows hyperinflation and a flattened diaphragm, while spirometry reveals a FEV1/FVC ratio of 55%, consistent with obstructive lung disease.
actual_diagnosis: 1. Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, ICD-10 code J44.9

doctor_vignette: A 71-year-old male presents with increased thirst and frequent urination over the past month. On physical examination, he is found to have dry skin and a high respiratory rate. Laboratory results reveal a fasting blood glucose level of 250 mg/dL and HbA1c of 9.5%. Ketones are present in his urine, indicating potential diabetic ketoacidosis.
actual_diagnosis: 2. Type 1 diabetes mellitus, ICD-10 code E10.9

doctor_vignette: A 107-year-old female presents with persistent fatigue and a rash on her face that resembles a butterfly shape. Physical examination reveals joint swelling in her hands and a low-grade fever. Laboratory tests show elevated antinuclear antibodies (ANA) and a positive anti-double-stranded DNA test, confirming autoimmune activity.
actual_diagnosis: 4. Systemic lupus erythematosus, ICD-10 code M32.9

doctor_vignette: A 99-year-old male presents to the emergency department with acute chest pain radiating to his left arm and shortness of breath. On physical examination, he is diaphoretic, with a blood pressure of 90/60 mmHg and a heart rate of 110 bpm. An ECG shows ST-segment elevation in the anterior leads, and cardiac troponin levels are markedly elevated. His history includes hypertension and a prior myocardial infarction.
actual_diagnosis: 3. Acute myocardial infarction, ICD-10 code I21.9

doctor_vignette: A 68-year-old male presents with exertional dyspnea and fatigue. On examination, he has elevated blood pressure of 160/100 mmHg, a left ventricular heave, and an S4 gallop rhythm. An echocardiogram reveals left ventricular hypertrophy, and his B-type natriuretic peptide (BNP) level is elevated at 300 pg/mL.
actual_diagnosis: 5. Hypertensive heart disease, ICD-10 code I11.9

doctor_vignette: A 39-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of shortness of breath and wheezing that worsens at night and with exercise. Physical examination reveals expiratory wheezes and prolonged expiratory phase on auscultation. Spirometry shows a reduced FEV1/FVC ratio, indicating airflow obstruction that improves with bronchodilator administration.
